note: [TRUE START TIME 2024-05-04T06:36Z IN LASCO C2 - RETAINING COR2A/T06:53Z START TIME AS NOTIFICATION SENT PRIOR TO UPDATE]. CME to the NE, only seen in STEREO COR2A and later in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 after a delayed backfill. Associated with an M9.1-class flare from AR 3663 (N26W09) which peaked at 2024-05-04T06:19Z, best observed in SDO AIA 131. Also observed as an EUV wave and field line movement deflected to the NE of the region in SDO AIA 171/193/211.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Loop CME seen to the NW in only SOHO LASCO C2/C3, due to a data gap in STEREO COR2A. The source is uncertain, with the only potential source being some field line movement in SDO AIA 171, slowly beginning around 2024-05-04T09:19Z and lasting a few hours. This is well before the observed CME time however, so that lowers confidence in this source. Otherwise, no other EUV signatures observed.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: [TRUE START TIME 2024-05-05T01:12Z IN LASCO C2 - RETAINING COR2A/T02:09Z START TIME AS NOTIFICATION SENT PRIOR TO UPDATE]. Narrow northern CME with filamentary structures which is similar to some previous CMEs from AR 3663. This CME is very likely associated with the M9.0 and M8.4 flares from AR 3663, peaking at 2024-05-04T23:48Z and 2024-05-05T01:27Z respectively, however no clear additional lower coronal signatures have been found in EUV imagery. This CME appears as two separately emerging fronts (T01:12Z and T02:12Z) which combine early in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery--which has now backfilled as of 2024-05-07 that prevented full real-time analysis for flare association.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely related to the eruption and subsequent X1.2 flare from Active Region 13663 (N26W23) seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery starting around 2024-05-05T12:00Z. Field line opening is visible at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A faint CME to the SE with multiple successive fronts/outflows. It may be associated with the flaring activity in AR 3664 (S19E18) and AR 3668 that was sympathetic to higher intensity (M-class) flaring in AR 3663. In terms of coronal signatures, there is a flare in/south of AR 3664 starting around 2024-05-05T14:30Z and a dimming in AIA 193 south of the AR, as well as some post-eruptive arcades following it. A separate smaller dimming appears at S30E05 and could be responsible for the more western brighter front/edge of the front in coronagraph. The CME is fully covered by a data gap in STEREO.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME with H-alpha emissions, where the source is a significant filament eruption behind the northwest limb, best seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-05-05T16:32Z. We can also see the ejecta faintly behind the limb in AIA 304 and 171. There is also an opening of field lines seen in AIA 193 at the same time. We are not able to see any post-eruptive arcades on the limb, so this CME is likely far behind the limb. The CME is completely covered by the evening data gap in STEREO A imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME with a brighter bulk and a faint, also narrow, preceding shock. Its source is likely the X4.5 flare from AR 3663 (N26W35), with an eruption signified by rising post-eruptive arcades after the flare. There are some signs of an EUV wave in AIA 193, but they are very faint.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faint and narrow but visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to a small eruption/brightening from S12E75 which appears to exhibit a southern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 304 imagery at 2024-05-07T01:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Earth-directed full halo seen in all coronagraphs. The source is a large eruption from AR 3664, which included two flares seen in SDO AIA 131, an initial M3.5 (S21W10) followed by the main long-duration X1.0 (S22W10) which peaked at 2024-05-08T04:30Z and 2024-05-08T05:09Z respectively. An EUV wave and field line movement is observed in SDO AIA 94/131/171/211 with some surface brightening in SDO AIA 304. This flare+CME combo resulted in a small rise in protons observed at SOHO and GOES, but not enough for a threshold crossing.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Earth-directed full halo seen in all coronagraphs. The source is a large eruption from AR 3664, which included a long-duration M8.6 flare (S22W11) which peaked at 2024-05-08T12:04Z best seen in SDO AIA 131. An EUV wave and field line movement is observed in SDO AIA 94/131/171/211 with some surface brightening in SDO AIA 304. This flare+CME combo resulted in a small rise in protons observed at SOHO and GOES, but not enough for a threshold crossing. The start time used here is when the shock front emerges, with the brighter bulk front emerging ~2024-05-08T13:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in STEREO A COR2 for a few frames prior to and following a data gap lasting from 2024-05-08T19:53Z to 2024-05-09T01:53Z. The source is a filament eruption near Active Region 13667 (N26E22) starting around 2024-05-08T18:07Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Filament material can be seen against the backdrop of the East limb as the material continues to leave the field of view in SDO AIA 304 around 19:35Z. A large dimming area is seen in SDO AIA 193 at this time, which appears to move southwest of the eruption site. Additionally, some post-eruptive arcades are seen in SDO AIA 171/193 starting around 20:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Full halo CME with a bulk portion visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery following a data gap in STEREO A COR2 lasting from 2024-05-08T19:53Z to 2024-05-09T01:53Z. The source is a large eruption and accompanying X1.0 and M9.8 flares from Active Region 13664 (S20W17) staring around 2024-05-08T21:08Z. Two rising loops are seen from Active Region 13664 (S20W17) staring around 2024-05-08T21:29Z and 22:08Z, respectively, as seen in SDO AIA 193/131, which likely resulted in two leading edges which very quickly combine in early frames of SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, and thus are considered one CME. A wide EUV wave and widely opening field lines are seen in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Halo CME visible in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This halo is associated with the X2.2 class flare from AR13664 peaking at 2024-05-09T09:13Z. A clear EUV wave is visible in SDO/AIA 193 and 211 crossing towards the central meridian and towards the limb in the southwest. Post-eruptive arcades are present in SDO/AIA 193 and 131. Brightening is visible in SDO/AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Partial halo CME associated with an X1.1 flare from AR 3664 (S18W29) with a full halo faint shock and slightly brighter fuzzy-fronted bulk. The start time is possibly earlier that 18:23Z  as the start of this event is covered by a data gap in SOHO due to a maneuver. Coronal signatures include a large ejecta from AR 3664 seen starting north-westwards ~17:36ZZ in AIA 304, a significant-area dimming mostly extending northward and westward of the flare location and stretching as far as the two coronal holes north of the equator.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible as an asymmetrical halo directed primarily towards the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an eruption and X3.9 flare from Active Region 13664 (S18W37) starting around 2024-05-10T06:45Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. An EUV wave is seen in SDO AIA 193 imagery extending to north of the flare to N20W40 and east to S25E20. Post eruptive arcades begin to form around 2024-05-10T08:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint CME partially overlapping with 2024-05-10T21:28Z CME and other outflows/fronts. No clear source was found on disk but there are some signs of smaller eruptions along a very long filament centered loosely around S35E01 to the east of Active Region 13664. The filament seems to finally erupt after 2024-05-10T21Z. This CME is fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A narrow faint CME to the south with an uncertain source. It might be associated with some eruptive activities occurring along a very long filament centered loosely around S35E01 to the east of AR 3664 which finally erupts after 21Z: the area close to filament center shows eruptive  activity/dimming/restructuring around 16Z, 18Z and after 20Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Ear-shaped bright partial halo CME with a very complex shape brighter bulk and a fainter somewhat asymmetric full halo shock. The CME is associated with the X5.8 flare and a significant eruption (massive dimming) and EUV wave seen in SDO 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint front to the West following the 2024-05-11T01:36Z CME. The source was not found on the disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery following M8.8 class flare from AR13664. The source is clearly visible in SDO/AIA wavelengths (193/171/304/211/94/131/335) and in STEREO A EUVI 195. There is clear dimming towards the coronal hole to the north of the active region as well as a minor EUV wave towards the north.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is wide and fast field line movement from well beyond the SE limb, first seen at 2024-05-12T01:36Z in SDO AIA 171 as well as in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This wide flux rope CME is seen to the SW in all three coronagraphs. The source is field line movement and ejecta from well beyond the SW limb: field line movement visible starting around 2024-05-12T02:49Z in SDO AIA 193; some ejecta seen from beyond the SW limb in SDO AIA 304 starting around 02:20Z; ejecta, filamentary material, and moving field lines visible at 03:33Z in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Full asymmetric halo CME seen to the SW in all three coronagraphs. Source is a large eruption and several M-class flares from Active Region 13664, including a long-duration M4.9 flare associated with the post-eruptive arcades. Widely opening field lines and a rising loop of ejecta seen starting at 2024-05-13T08:10Z in SDO AIA 193/171. Ejecta and post-eruptive brightening and arcades seen at 08:43Z in SDO AIA 131/304. Post eruptive arcades seen at 11:15Z in SDO AIA 171/193/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Lopsided CME seen to the W in all coronagraphs. The CME front has an interesting point-shaped nose, but this is much fainter than the faint bright front which is somewhat lopsided to the S. Source is an X1.7 flare from AR 3664 which peaked at 2024-05-14T02:09Z, seen best in SDO AIA 131. Also observed as fast, wide opening field lines and small EUV wave in SDO AIA 171/193/211 starting around 2024-05-14T02:07Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen to the SE in all coronagraphs. Source is uncertain, with what could be an on-disk source that does not line up well when used in measurement. Observed well as field line movement over the SE limb in SDO AIA 171/193/211 starting around 2024-05-14T04:06Z. Additionally, a smaller C6.5 flare which peaked at 2024-05-14T04:08Z observed in SDO AIA 131 (this flare does not rise high above background flux, but is distinct in EUV imagery) lines up with this timestamp and the field line movement, but the source coordinates did not work well in swpc_cat triangulation to support it. It is possible that the source for this CME is on/just beyond the SE limb, supported by better triangulation at those longitudes.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs (STEREO A gets first visible frame). Source is an unnumbered region of the solar disk, centered around N23E35. Starting around 2024-05-14T09:07Z, field line movement is observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 alongside a diagonal region of light dimming spanning approximately N40E60 -> N15E30 across that center point. A distinct post-eruptive arcade forms around 2024-05-14T10:47Z across SDO AIA 131/171/193/211.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This irregularly shaped CME is seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is likely near Active Region 13664 which was at about W90-95 at the time of this eruption. Source is one of several instances of opening field lines seen on the SW limb at about S20 starting at 2024-05 14T08:30Z and lasting through 2024-05-14T10:30Z. The most likely occurrence of field line movement to be associated with this CME is seen in GOES SUVI 304 at 09:12Z. Field line movement is also seen in SDO AIA 193 at 08:48Z and in GOES SUIV 284 at 08:44Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the W in all coronagraphs. Source is an X1.2 flare from AR 3664 (located at S19W94 at this time, just beyond the limb) which peaked at 2024-05-14T12:55Z, best seen in SDO AIA 131. Also observed as rapidly opening field lines and a small EUV wave in SDO AIA 171/193/211 around 2024-05-14T12:49Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME from behind the west limb, the first in a series of two closely following CMEs. Its source is the occulted X8.7 flare from AR 3664, just over the limb. Coronal signatures include a massive EUV wave and field line movement/restructuring of magnetic field behind the limb across wide range of latitudes (mass seen departing) beginning ~2024-05-14T16:49Z, field line movement seen across every wavelength. Very fast opening of the field lines likely associated with this CME is best seen in AIA 335 starting at 16:50Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME to the west which closely follows the preceding faster and slightly narrower 2024-05-14T17:0Z CME. The source of this second CME could be the long filament eruption off/behind the west limb best seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-05-14T17:02Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very wide eruption to the NE in all coronagraphs, notably bright with a twisted flux-rope structure beautifully observed in SOHO LASCO C2. The source is an eruption from new AR 3682, associated with an M4.4 class flare observed in SDO AIA 131. Also observed as field line movement and EUV wave in SDO AIA 171/193/211 starting around 2024-05-14T17:09Z, with a post-eruptive arcade forming shortly after. A massive loop is seen well in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-05-14T17:33Z before it erupts further, not seen often at that scale.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME seen due West in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is EUV wave seen beyond the SW limb starting at 2024-05-15T08:18Z in SDO AIA 171/193. Widely opening field lines with northern deflection seen on or just beyond the SW limb at an apparent latitude of S15 (before deflection). This CME overlaps heavily with CME: 2024-05-15T08:48Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast CME seen to the WSW in all coronagraphs, overlaps with CME 2024-05-15T08:36Z. The source is an X3.4 flare (partially occulted) from AR 3664 that peaked at 2024-05-15T08:37Z, observed in SDO AIA 131/193/304, and located around the west limb at approximately W100-W105 at this time. Additionally observed source signature as large EUV wave in SDO AIA 171/193/211/304 starting around 2024-05-15T08:18Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is a faint but distinct loop visible to the West in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. A distinct source for this CME is not discernable in UV imagery, so it is likely beyond the West limb. This CME is preceded by two much larger CMEs (2024-05-15T08:36Z and 2024-05-15T08:48Z) with source locations that are clearly beyond the limb and are measured to have similar speeds to this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the NNE in all coronagraphs. Observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as a loop centered over an unnumbered region on the disk ~N35E35. This loop slowly begins rising around 2024-05-16T06:30Z before explosively erupting and breaking around 2024-05-16T09:15Z. A broad area of dimming to the N and E of this area is observed in SDO AIA 193 with the eruption, a double ribbon flare is observed in SDO AIA 304 underneath this loop, and a post-eruptive arcade starts forming around 2024-05-16T10:09Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is seen to the W/SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is a distinct loop of material (a flux rope) seen slowly rising from on or just beyond the SW limb, at an apparent latitude of S25, starting at 2024-05-15T10:00Z in SDO AIA 171/193 as well as in GOES SUVI 284/304/193. The longitude of candidate source location Active Region 13664 was at approximately W105. This CME is visible in only a few frames of STEREO A COR2 due to a short data gap lasting from 2024-05-15T12:23Z-13:38Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen to the SE in all coronagraphs. A data gap in SOHO that will not backfill from 2024-05-15T13:36Z - 2024-05-15T16:05Z in C2 (T13:40Z-T16:30Z in C3) missed a large portion of the event, but it is still observed in later frames. Associated with an X2.9 flare from new AR 3685 which peaked at 2024-05-15T14:38Z in SDO AIA 131. Also observed as wide field line opening and EUV wave in SDO AIA 171/193/211 with a post-eruptive arcade across all wavelengths, both observed around 2024-05-15T14:20Z with the flare start time.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not clearly visible in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source can be seen as opening field lines starting at 2024-05-15T20:39Z best seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284. A potential candidate active region is Active Region 13664, located around approximately W110.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. A source was not clearly visible in EUV imagery, but a candidate source may be old Active Region 3664.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not clear in EUV imagery, and this CME may be backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not clear in EUV imagery, and this CME may be backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is unclear, but faint opening field lines and some brightening can be seen around S15E70 in SDO AIA 193 starting around 2024-05-16T07:00Z. The eruption is not clearly visible in STEREO A EUV imagery or other wavelengths.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the W in STEREO COR2A, not yet observed in SOHO LASCO due to a lengthy planned data gap that will end at 2024-05-17T02:10Z. The source is far-sided around the west limb, and very likely old AR 3664, estimated to be located around W120 at this time. Best observed as fieldline movement and an EUV wave starting around 2024-05-16T13:34Z in SDO AIA 171/193/211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright three-lobed (and hence wide) heart-shaped northern CME fully covered by a night time data gap in STEREO. Its source is likely a super faint movement of a field line and a movement of matter on the NNW front at 18:54Z seen only in AIA 171 possibly confirming that the CME is backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME in the NNW. No clear source has been found for it although there is some very minor dimming in the north and also a movement of field line on the NNW limb around 23:50Z but both are inconclusive.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint narrow outflow with unclear front. The source is likely Active Region 3664 located at ~128 deg.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the south. No clear source found on disk, although there is eruption in AR 3683 after 03:00Z (S23W23) but this seems too far to the west.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow western CME following 2024-05-17T00:12Z CME. Coronal signature of this CME is seen in the west in AIA 193 as opening/moving of field lines after 03:33Z. The source is likely Active Region 3664 located at ~130 deg.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, faint CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Potentially associated with AR 3679. A filament eruption is visible in this area around 2024-05-17T03:00Z in SDO AIA 304 which appears to deflect to the north in EUV imagery. Dimming and post eruptive arcades are visible in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME seen to the west. A backsided source is indicated for it by a massive and fast restructuring of magnetic field behind the west limb which is seen at 2024-05-17T12:38Z in SDO AIA 171 and less prominently in AIA 193. The source is likely the former Active Region  13664 which is now at the longitude of 135 degrees. The backsided flare is confirmed by the STIX instrument at the Solar Orbiter which saw a significant flare.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This faint, narrow, and irregularly shaped CME is seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The only discernible source may be some very small ejecta from just beyond the SW limb at an apparent latitude of S20 or so, visible in GOES SUVI 304 at 2024-05-17T18:34Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This heart-shaped CME is seen to the E/SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. This CME is not observed by STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap lasting from 2024-05-17T20:53Z to 2024-05-18T01:23Z. Associated with the M7.2 flare from AR 13685 (S13E52). Widely opening field lines, an EUV wave, and post-eruptive arcade can be seen in SDO AIA 171/193 starting at 2024-05-17T20:54Z, and ejecta and brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 304/171. This eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 195 at 2024-0517T20:55Z as widely opening field lines and brightening, and in STEREO A EUVI 304 at 21:15Z as ejecta, brightening, and post-eruptive arcades.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note:
A somewhat asymmetric full halo CME with two consecutive fronts seen best in SOHO LASCO C3 (but also in C2). With the exception of one (or two) early timestamps this event is covered by a large gap in STEREO A COR2. The indication of the backsided source of this halo in EUV imagery is possibly a faint and very fast movement of field lines that likely happens far behind the east limb seen starting 2024-06-01T18:39Z in AIA 171 in the ESE. 
The backsided analysis is supported by the location of a large backsided active region in helioseismology imagery from GONG - likely the former AR 13679 that was around lat/lon -8/-170 at the time of this event. In addition, STIX instrument on the Solar Orbiter detected a significant flare (equivalent of GOES X1)peaking at 2024-06-01T18:45Z.
Identifying the coronal signatures of this CME is complicated by an almost simultaneous X1.0 class flare from Active Region 13697 on the Earth-facing disk followed by a later M7.3 flare from the same front-sided Active Region. The front-sided flares are accompanied by relatively weak coronal signatures of eruption - dimming and post-eruptive arcades.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A CME to the SE with a complex uneven (pointy) front that comes on the heels of and overlaps with the preceding 2024-06-01T19:12Z halo CME (which was concluded to be backsided). The source of this, likely front-sided, CME could be the M7.3 flare from Active Region 3697 (S20E21) peaking at 2024-06-01T19:40Z and an associated eruption signified by post-eruptive arcades and a somewhat more eastern, not very deep, dimming centered very approximately around (S20E25). The front (e.g. the width) of this CME is not easy to determine because of the overlap with the preceding, likely backsided, halo and because the CME is partially obscured by the pylon in C3.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

Both movements are seen in AIA 193 and 335.

The source for this CME is uncertain with no distinct source observed, and could potentially be related to some outflow from AR 3697 following large CME 2024-06-08T01:53Z.

note: Wide filament eruption seen to the SW in all coronagraphs. Source is a filament eruption from the far-side of the disk, observed best as the filament material itself in SDO AIA 304 launching around 2024-06-10T22:30Z from around S30-S40. The filament material appears to be closer to the limb, but is accompanied by a wider far-sided field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193/211 that appears further around the limb. This is corroborated by the fit in swpc_cat between SOHO and STEREO coronagraphs not working unless longitudes >W130 were used. It appears that two fronts are traveling together from this front--perhaps the filament and field line movements--and are thus measured as one for this analysis.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs, but only briefly in STEREO COR2A as it enters a data gap after the first few frames. This CME front was quite difficult to analyze due to the source activity--two simultaneous filament eruptions in the NW with one visible front. The first filament spanning N45W25<->N41W34 began lifting around 2024-06-18T14:00Z and erupting more explosively around 2024-06-18T16:00Z in SDO 304, leaving behind a broad double ribbon flare in SDO AIA 304 and dimming in SDO AIA 171/193/211 centered around N59W34, with a post-eruptive arcade forming around 2024-06-18T16:40Z in SDO AIA 171/193/211. The second filament was a prominence over the NW limb, which began destabilizing around 2024-06-18T12:40Z and erupting around 2024-6-18T16:40Z in SDO 304 followed by a post-eruptive arcade visible over the limb in SDO AIA 171/193/211 starting around 2024-06-18T18:00Z. A potential second front was observed ~380 km/s with a fitted source of N35W25, but this is uncertain, but noting this observation due to the missing secondary front we would expect with two filaments.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. There are 2 candidate sources for this eruption. The first is weak dimming/post eruptive arcades in a broad area centered around S43E18 in SDO AI AIA 193, gradually starting around 2024-06-18T02:21Z. Another potential source starts earlier, at about 2024-06-18T16:16Z, and is seen around S25E60 as an ejecta of material.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: First of two paired CMEs seen to the W in all coronagraphs (this one is more northern), following an M1.1 flare which peaked at 2024-06-19T06:38Z from AR 3711 seen in SDO AIA 131 with some field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171/193/211 at this time. Two fronts appear to travel out from this eruption, both only fitting near this source but fitting far enough apart in lat/lon to warrant two separate entries (see CME 2024-06-19T07:00Z). Interestingly, this eruption did not look too impressive in SDO AIA imagery, but far-sided fits of the fronts proved far worse than using this source longitude, so higher confidence is granted in this source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Second of two paired CMEs seen to the SW in all coronagraphs (this one is more southern), following an M1.1 flare which peaked at 2024-06-19T06:38Z from AR 3711 seen in SDO AIA 131 with some field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171/193/211 at this time. Two fronts appear to travel out from this eruption, both only fitting near this source but fitting far enough apart in lat/lon to warrant two separate entries (see CME 2024-06-19T06:48Z). Interestingly, this eruption did not look too impressive in SDO AIA imagery, but far-sided fits of the fronts proved far worse than using this source longitude, so higher confidence is granted in this source. Both fronts unfortunately appeared in SOHO LASCO C2 at the same frame, so this CME was bumped to T07:00Z to avoid the overlap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a partial halo to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. A wide opening of field lines is visible near the eastern limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at this time as well. Based on GONG far-sided imagery, it is possible this eruption occurred from former Active Region 13697. This region would have been located around longitude -110 to -115 degrees at the time of this event based on the rate of solar rotation.

note: Bright 3-part CME with an even wider shock front. The start of the CME might be a bit earlier but it is more likely that there is a preceding front of a narrower precursor CME that gets swept into the 2024-06-24T02:48Z CME. The clear source of this CME is an eruption starting around 2024-06-24T01Z off of or behind the SW limb and seen as an unusually long/persistant brightening off of the SW limb seen in AIA 131/335 between 2024-06-24T01Z and as opening  of field lines on/behind the SW limb in AIA 193/171 starting after 2024-06-24T01Z. The opening of field lines starts as relatively narrow but becomes wider after 2024-06-24T02Z and is followed by very high rising post-eruptive arcades seen  on/just behind the SW limb. It is likely that the eruption is from Active Region 3712 which was at ~S25W91 at the time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This faint CME is seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. No discernable source signatures are visible in SDO AIA or GOES SUVI imagery. This eruption possibly correlates to an estimated M1.0 flare observed in STIX data, with estimated peak time at roughly 2024-08-11T06:24Z and located beyond on SE limb of the Earth-facing disk (on the SW limb as seen from Solar Orbiter). This CME overlaps with CME:2024-08-11T07:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and extremely faintly in STEREO A COR2. This CME overlaps with CME:2024-08-11T07:00Z; both CMEs are believed to be from the same source. No discernable source signatures are visible in SDO AIA or GOES SUVI imagery. This eruption possibly correlates to an estimated M1.0 flare observed in STIX data, with estimated peak time at roughly 2024-08-11T06:24Z and located beyond on SE limb of the Earth-facing disk (on the SW limb as seen from Solar Orbiter).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Thin CME seen to the SE in all coronagraphs. Source is a region of the disk centered ~S36E50, with an eruption observed in SDO AIA 304 as thin ejecting filament material and brightening of the surface starting around 2024-08-12T07:33Z, with field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193/211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the NE in all coronagraphs. Source is a region of the disk centered ~N35E75, with an eruption observed as brightening of the disk in SDO AIA 304 starting around 2024-08-12T08:42Z, and field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193/211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, jet-like CME first seen in the S by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-12T12:36Z, as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this eruption is a jet of material seen clearly in GOES SUVI 304 lifting off from approx. S20E90 beginning at approximately 2024-08-12T12:00Z exhibiting strong Southern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME first seen to the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-12T19:00Z as well as in later frames by C3. There is no STEREO A COR2 data available due to a data gap from 2024-08-12T14:38Z to 2024-08-12T22:38Z. Possible source of this eruption is field line opening from AR 3780 (S11W30) exhibiting Southern deflection beginning at approximately 2024-08-12T18:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-12T21:48Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a jet of material seen in GOES SUVI 304 beginning at approximately 19:30Z from the vicinity of S30W90 but exhibiting Southeastern deflection. Field line opening can also be seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. There is no STEREO A EUVI data for this source signature due to a data gap from 2024-08-12T14:05Z to 2024-08-12T22:55Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint halo, with the front not seen in white light imagery but seen distinctly in SOHO difference imagery, both C2 and C3 (and not only in the early timestamps). The event is fully covered by a large data gap in STEREO A COR2. Its source could potentially be the faint eruption north of AR 3774 centered around (N28E12) and seen as very minor light dimming in AIA 193 between 2024-08-13T08Z and 14Z, however these coronal signatures seem too faint for a noticeable halo. Alternatively, the source could be far-sided. No coronal signatures indicating backsided CME have been found on/behind limb in AIA imagery, but there is a long-duration C8-class flare on the far side seen by STIX instrument on Solar Orbiter and peaking around 13:40Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet-like CME first seen to the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-14T03:48Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source appears to be a small filament eruption located at approx. S30W100 beginning around 2024-08-14T01:50Z exhibiting a more Southern deflection as seen in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraph imagery. The source is likely an M4.4 flare and eruption from Active Region 13777 (S04W89) starting around 2024-08-14T03:40Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. An opening of field lines is visible near the western limb at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 05:30Z as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: First CME in a series of consecutive CMEs to the west in both coronagraphs. No coronal signatures on disk have been found; there are some coronal signatures indicating that there were multiple eruptions around this time on/behind the limb, but these consecutive CMEs do not fit with two coronagraphs with longitudes close to/above 90 degrees.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a partial halo directed towards the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is visible mostly to the northeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an X1.1 flare and eruption from Active Region 13784 (N14E03) starting around 2024-08-14T06:27Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is observed in SDO AIA 171 and 193 surrounding the eruption site, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 08:30Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint jet-like CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-14T09:12Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STEREO A COR2. There is no clear source seen on the Earth facing disk, however some faint field line opening can be seen in SDO AIA 193, leading to a likely far sided source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Second in a series of consecutive CMEs to the west in both coronagraphs with no coronal signatures on disk but measuring about 65 deg long.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Forth in a series of consecutive CMEs to the west in both coronagraphs with no coronal signatures on disk but measuring about 65 deg long.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Extremely faint and narrow CME seen to the E in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2. Extremely faint in C3. Source is opening field lines on the E limb seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-08-14T23:30Z, from AR 13790 (S10E80).
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME in the northwest. Its clear source is a beautiful eruption that looks like a loop and is seen on or just behind the northwest limb starting around 2024-08-15T09:30Z, according to the SDO AIA 304/171 and GOES SUVI 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the W/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be the M1.3 flare from AR13780, however there are moving/opening field lines visible beyond the NW limb starting around 2024-08-16T13:31Z in GOES SUVI 284 that could also be a potential source for this CME. For this analysis, the M1.3 location was used with potential northern deflection visible in SDO/AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and a few frames within a data gap of STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be filament ejecta visible along the western limb starting around 2024-08-17T18:53Z best seen in SDO/AIA and GOES SUVI 304. There are moving/opening field lines also visible starting around 2024-08-17T19:00Z in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The start of this CME is likely much earlier but the front is not seen in C2. It is another (the narrowest) outflow from the fast 2024-08-17T19:12Z CME. The start of this CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2; its front is not seen in C2 difference imagery, but is seen in C3 and later COR2A difference imagery as a narrow blip. No source has been found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery for a few frames before the leading edge becomes too diffuse to follow. The source is likely related to faint field line movement visible near the southwest limb in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193 imagery starting around 2024-08-19T08:40Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as a wide opening of field lines are visible beyond the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery starting around 2024-08-19T12:20Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME partially overlaps with CME 2024-08-19T12:36Z. The source is likely far-sided as faint opening of field lines are visible beyond the northwest limb, just north of the opening field lines attributed to the overlapping CME, in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery starting around 2024-08-19T12:20Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is not clear. There is filament ejecta visible to the S/SE starting around 2024-08-20T16:45Z which isn't best for timing, however with limited stereoscopic viewpoints of the solar disk, it's possible there was an earlier eruption and the filament ejecta was seen later, this is very speculative though.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The first of three overlapping CMEs seen to the West in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is opening field lines from just beyond the West limb at an apparent latitude of S10 seen starting at 2024-08-19T21:49Z in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The second of three overlapping CMEs, seen to the Northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is wide but extremely faint opening field lines seen on or possibly just beyond the Northwest limb seen starting at 2024-08-19T21:03Z in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The third of three overlapping CMEs, seen to the Southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is widely and distinctly opening field lines from beyond the Southwest limb seen starting at 2024-08-19T21:54Z in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, fast CME seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO COR2A is not in a data gap but does not observe this CME, likely due to the faint nature. The source for this CME is uncertain, and may only be observed in SDO AIA 171 around 2024-08-20T07:12Z as some dimming in the field lines over the SE limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-20T11:48Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STERO A COR2. There is no clear source on the disk for this event, however some faint field line movement can be seen in GOES SUVI 284, so this is likely a far sided event. This CME partially overlaps with CME: 2024-08-20T12:12Z
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-20T12:12Z as well as in later frames by C3 and STERO A COR2. The source of this eruption is a filament eruption just beyond the West limb (approx. S30W120) as seen in STEREO A EUVI 304. Wide opening field lines can also be seen in SDO AIA 94, 171, 192 and GOES SUVI 284. This CME partially overlaps with CME: 2024-08-20T11:48Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright loop CME first seen to the NW in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-08-22T06:53Z. Data gap in SOHO LASCO imagery from 2024-08-21T23:36Z to 2024-08-22T07:24Z obstructed a few early frames of this CME in SOHO LASCO C2. The source of this event appears to be a large far-sided eruption, evidenced by wide opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284 beginning at approximately 2024-08-22T06:19Z and the possible remnants of filamentary material seen in GOES SUVI 304.
