No corresponding source has been found on the Earth-facing disk. There was an equivalent of an M3 class flare seen by STIX instrument on the Solar Orbiter peaking at 2024-08-22T14:37Z with the very approximate longitude of 180, which could be the far sided possible source of this CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and northwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no corresponding source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast, faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The source appears to be jet-like filament eruptions on or around the west limb, best observed in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-08-23T14:56Z, with a second one at 16:20Z less likely due to timing.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Streamer blowout CME to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The start time of the CME could be as early as ~10Z, as that's when the shape first starts appearing in difference imagery, however it doesn't quite start progressing out in the field of view until roughly 12:12Z. The source appears to be moving/opening field lines visible in GOES SUVI 284 in the SE quadrant of the Earth-facing disk with notable changes in the corona's structure over the course of several hours. Most notably, these changes are visible starting around 14:00Z. Brightening is visible on the disk starting around 15:00Z with continued restructuring of the corona for several hours after. Additionally, the CME structure appears to be visible in the field lines off the SE limb, fairly stationary as early as 2024-08-25T17:00Z and is released during this restructuring starting around 2024-08-26T12:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-28T04:12Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is the eruption of a loop like filament sitting on or just beyond the East limb centered at approximately S10E90 as seen in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195, along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94 and 131. This filament erupted in two portions, the first appearing as a streamer outflow, followed by the main expulsion of material. In the coronagraphs, this appears as two leading edges, a further out one that is lopsided and faint and a closer in one that is more central and bright. Parameters of this event are based on the more central, brightest portion of this CME, as that is where the bulk of the material resides.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-08-28T11:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk apart from some minor field line movement seen in the NE in SDO AIA 171. Event does not exhibit a clear and distinct leading edge.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the southeast which possibly consists of two lobes: an earlier, more eastern lobe, and a later, narrower, lobe, directed somewhat more to the south. The source of this CME is the fast opening of and movement of field lines in the corona behind the southeast limb directed, as well as dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 at 2024-08-30T12:27Z. This eruption was also associated with the M3.8 flare from Active Region 13806. There was also a slightly later, slower, eruption from the southeast limb (or from behind the limb), which is seen in SDO AIA 193 after 2024-08-30T12:30Z and which is characterized by a minor ejecta best seen in SDO AIA 304, followed by an opening of field lines behind the limb seen in AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the W in all coronagraphs, but best in STEREO COR2A. The source is not completely clear, and may be a part of some field line movement on/around the west limb in SDO AIA 171 beginning as early as 2024-08-30T18:22Z. This CME is notably extremely faint in SOHO imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source is far-sided, observed best as field line movement over the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 starting around 2024-08-30T23:42Z, with secondary more northern movement seen starting around 2024-08-31T00:12Z which likely resulted in 2024-08-31T00:53Z. This CME's parameters are difficult to pin down, due to an ongoing campaign with SOHO impacting available LASCO C2/C3 imagery for triangulation with STEREO COR2A.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This asymmetrical shaped CME is visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery due to a campaign. The source appears to be moving/opening field lines from beyond the NE limb in SDO/AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-08-31T11:09Z. Multiple loops are seen rising in SDO/AIA 171 which may contribute to the appearance of multiple fronts in coronagraph imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is a large eruption on the SE limb seen as brightening starting at 2024-09-01T11:06Z in SDO AIA 131, ejection of material at 11:18Z in SDO AIA 304, rapidly opening field lines seen beyond the limb starting at 11:30Z in SDO AIA 171/193. Slow rise and eventual ejection of two overlapping flux rope loops from the southeast limb seen starting as early as 2024-09-01T08:08Z in GOES SUVI 304. Long-duration M5.5 flare associated with brightening from post-eruptive arcades that spanned from S20-S30, as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the S/SE following the path of the 2024-09-01T12:23Z CME in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. No clear visible source in SDO/AIA or GOES/SUVI imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption close to the East limb, N15E65, seen starting at 2024-09-02T05:30Z in SDO AIA 171/193, followed by moving/opening field lines seen starting at 2024-09-02T06:03 in SDO AIA 171, as well as post-eruptive arcade starting at 2024-09-02T07:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the east in SOHO C2 and STEREO A, but more predominantly in SOHO imagery, later overlapping with CME:2024-09-02T14:00Z which is seen to the southeast. Seemingly associated with an eruption occurring just before the CME: 2024-09-02T14:00Z from near the same region or farther behind the limb with clear northward deflection, however, fitting for longitudes between 60-70 is poor as the leading edges in SOHO/STEREO A do not overlap well in time, suggesting that this CME is more far-sided than anticipated. Farther longitudes behind the eastern disk do show a stronger leading edge fit and triangulation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. Associated with a contributing portion of an M2.9-class flare and eruption near AR 3813 (S17E62) seen best in SDO 304/193 as a brightening and in 171/193 as brightening with moving field lines. GOES 284 also shows a large bulb-shaped mass emanating from off the southeast limb after the initial brightening.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright full asymmetric halo CME in SOHO and a partial northwestern halo in STEREO A, with a fainter but distinct shock front in addition to a very bright bulk. Its source is likely farsided and is indicated by the faint but very wide opening of field lines/restructuring of magnetic field far behind the northwest (extending faintly to southwest) limb, as seen in SDO 193/171 starting at 2024-09-03T08:18Z, also seen in STA EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-03T14:48Z as well as in later frames by SOHO LASCO C3. There is no STEREO A COR2 data available for this event due to an ongoing data gap beginning 03/14:38Z with one frame at 03/17:23Z. There is no clear source for this CME seen on the disk, however some minor field line movement can be seen beyond the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 leading to the possibility of this being a far sided event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-03T15:12Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is limited COR2A data available for this event due to a data gap from 03/14:38Z to 03/17:23Z. The source of this CME is an eruption from AR 3807 (S18W54) beginning at approximately 03/14:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-03T20:12Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event is partially obscured in STEREO A by a data gap from 03/14:38Z to 03/22:53Z. The source of this CME is an area of dimming spanning from N25E30 to N10E03 but is centered around N10E20. Although a majority of the dimming appears to be more central, there are field lines that appear to open more towards the NE as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME seen to the northwest in SOHO C2/C3 then becoming more to the north with time. Also seen to the west-northwest in STEREO A COR2A. No obvious sources are seen on the Earth facing disk or off the northwestern limb, so this CME event is likely far-sided relative to the Sun-Earth line.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fairly symmetrical halo CME with brighter portions to the NW in SOHO and NE in STEREO A, first seen around 2024-09-05T07:24Z in SOHO C2. The eruption is very likely on the far-side relative to the Earth-facing solar disk as evidenced by flickering field lines seen best in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 284 far off the northwest and southwest limbs seen around 2024-09-05T07:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the west. No source has been found on disk in EUV imagery. There is a minor eruptive activity seen on/behind the limb in EUV imagery. There are multiple secondary fronts following the initial front.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow, faint CME seen to the southwest in SOHO C2/STEREO A COR2 which may be associated with changes in departing Active Region 3807 (~W97) around 2024-09-06T11:00Z or so as seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor puff-like CME seen to the northwest in SOHO C2 and C3 and not seen with available STEREO A COR2 frames due to a data gap. Likely associated with a minor eruption seen near AR3806 (S12W46) seen best in GOES SUVI 304 with northward deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast, narrow CME seen to the south-southwest in SOHO C2, C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not clear, however, one potential source candidate is a filament eruption and surge eruption near the southern portion of the central meridian; it takes place near 16:05Z, which is fairly early compared to when the CME is first seen. Some weakly opening field lines seen best in GOES SUVI 284 just before 18:00Z off the south-southwestern limb could additionally be associated with this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and as a partial halo in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a filament eruption centered near N14W20 which deflects NW as it erupts based on SDO/AIA 304 imagery. The eruption begins around 2024-09-08T00:00Z. A faint EUV wave is visible traveling N/NE of the source location despite the filament material deflecting NW as seen in SDO/AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the W in C2 and STEREO A COR2. Not visible in C3. Leading edge appears brighter in STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO. Source is opening field lines seen at 2023-09-08T09:15Z just beyond the limb as seen in STEREO-A EUVI 304 and 195 imagery, at about S10.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large, bright lightbulb CME to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a long duration M1.0 flare from AR13806 (~S05W89). Moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 193 starting around 2024-09-09T00:24Z along the western limb with post-eruptive arcades visible starting around 2024-09-09T02:24Z. The eruption is also visible in GOES SUVI before an eclipse occurs and in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large bright halo CME with bulk to the NE in STEREO A COR2 and following a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The source appears to be beyond the eastern limb in SDO/AIA 193 and 211 starting around 2024-09-09T05:00Z with a visible rising loop and clear moving/opening field lines. There is a dimming/reconstruction/EUV wave in the coronal material along the limb. Possible filament material is visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 304 briefly around 2024-09-09T05:10Z. Moving field lines are briefly visible in GOES SUVI 284 before an eclipse occurs.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME associated with a long duration M1.2-class flare from Active Region 3814 (N15E10) seen predominantly to the northeast in SOHO C2 imagery and east-northeast in STEREO A COR2. The eruptive signature is seen as a large-broad scale destabilization seen as a surge-like brightening in SDO AIA 131, opening and brightening field lines in GOES SUVI 284 with additional dimming and an EUV wave to the north, and bright, high post-eruptive arcades seen best in SDO AIA 171/193/304. There is a data gap in real-time in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 at the start of the CME from approx. 2024-09-09T21:48Z to 2024-09-10T01:25Z
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-10T20:12Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a far sided filament eruption and resulting field line movement seen off the South limb in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284 and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by STEREO A COR2. There is currently no SOHO LASCO imagery for this event due to a data gap from 11/02:36Z to 11/07:12Z. The source of this event is an M1.0 class flare peaking at 2024-09-10T23:50Z and subsequent eruption from AR 3814 (N16W03) as seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 304. The flare peaked at 2024-09-10T23:50Z, however the eruption continued through approx. 11/01:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 304. Opening field lines, slight dimming and a possible EUV wave can be seen propagating towards the NE in SDO AIA 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 195. Due to the lack of SOHO data available to triangulate the source, there is some degree of uncertainty in the latitude and longitude of this CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint yet fast CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-11T16:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. There is no STEREO A COR2 data available for this event due to a data gap from 2024-09-11T14:38Z to 2024-09-11T22:23Z. The source of this event is an M1.8 class flare peaking at 2024-09-11T15:30Z and a subsequent fast eruption of material seen along the Eastern limb (approx. S20E90). The flare is seen clearly in SDO AIA 131, along with material seen leaving the disk in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line movement can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, lightbulb CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-12T21:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is clear rising loops and opening field lines seen off of the NE limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright wide CME off the southwest limb, likely associated with the M1.2 flare from AR 3811 (S13W91) peaking at 2024-0913T00:00Z. Coronal signatures include a large ejecta seen in AIA 131 and in SUVI 284 starting at 2024-0913T00:27Z and a wide opening of field lines on/behind the limb in SUVI 284 starting at 2024-0913T01:24Z. High-rising post-eruptive arcades are seen in AIA 193 on limb (and less prominently a few more southward on the disk).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, directly following CME: 2024-09-13T02:00Z in the field of view of the coronagraphs. The potential source is from the cluster of Active Regions in the southwest, with field line movement visible in STEREO A EUV 195 and SDO AIA 193 around 2024-09-13T04:35Z. Post-eruptive loops are visible for several hours following the eruption in SDO AIA 131, 171, and 193. Outflowing material is visible in the coronagraphs following this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with a clear front in the northwest in SOHO and north in STEREO A COR2, indicating its directedness towards STEREO A and a bit north. Likely source is is unspecified flaring south of AR 3814 (N12W33) around 2024-09-13T08:24Z, with a medium-sized dimming and post-eruptive arcades as coronal signatures. This eruption is right at the disk center in STEREO A EUV imagery. In EUVI A 304 we also see a small ejecta directed southwards. The flaring is unspecified because it coincides with a much more intense flaring from Active Region 3823 on southwest limb, so the intensity of this lesser flare cannot be measured.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The start time is in SOHO LASCO C2 after a data gap from 2024-09-13T13:48Z-15:12Z. The potential source is opening field lines and brightening loops seen on the west limb in SDO AIA 193. The activity starts around 2024-09-13T09:00Z and continues for several hours following the eruption. The activity is also visible from the point of view of STEREO A EUV imagery. Overlapping CMEs are visible in the coronagraphs around this time, and may also be from this activity to the west.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source location is likely field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171/193 on the west limb starting at 2024-09-13T15:28Z. Rising loops can also be seen from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide, bright CME seen to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 and in SOHO C2/C3 during a data gap. This CME is associated with a large scale eruption from the departing group of sunspots on the southwest limb as evidenced by the quickly and widely opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284 near 2024-09-14T03:36Z and ejecta seen in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Partial halo CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2/C3 and not yet observed in STEREO A due to a data gap. Associated with a powerful X4.5-class solar flare from AR3825 (S18E55) and subsequent strong eruption, characterized by intense brightening in SDO 131 and fast ejecta seen best in GOES SUVI 284 as well as a large, fast EUV wave associated with the eruption traversing back towards the northwest seen best in SDO AIA 171/193 that covers approximately half the solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-09-14T17:38Z-22:38Z. There is no clear source visible for this CME in available EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 from 2024-09-14T17:38Z to 2024-09-14T22:38Z. The source is not seen in EUV imagery. The CME follows directly after CME: 2024-09-14T19:36Z in the coronagraphs.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the NE better in STEREO COR2A, and seen barely in SOHO LASCO C2 due to diffuseness. There is no clear source for this CME on the disk, and due to a lengthy SOHO data gap in real time due to a keyhole maneuver not much imagery is available real-time for better triangulation.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint, narrow CME visible to the S/SE in SOHO imagery (SOHO imagery flips after midnight zulu, start time of CME based on first appearance in SOHO C2 in unrotated image) and to the S/SW in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears as moving/opening field lines along the southern limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-09-17T15:47Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-18T05:48Z as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, however some minor field line opening can be seen off of the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284, suggesting a far sided eruption. This CME does not have a distinct leading edge and significantly widens as it progresses.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-18T06:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, which corroborates a far sided measurement. Some minor field line movement can be seen off of the South limb in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-18T12:36Z, as well as by C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this CME is an eruption on or just beyond the SE limb seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193. Field line opening is visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195, as well as post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 131. This event is completely blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3 and is partially obscured in STEREO A due to a data gap beginning at 2024-09-18T14:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fuzzy CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain and unobserved in EUV imagery, but clearly lies far-sided via triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A in swpc_cat.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faint but visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. It is not seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap from 2024-09-19T21:53Z to 2024-09-20T00:23Z. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event. Faint field line movement may be visible beyond the NE limb in SDO AIA 171 imagery starting around 2024-09-19T21:40Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Thin diffuse CME seen to the NW in all coronagraphs. The source is best observed in SDO AIA 171 as field line movement on or just beyond the NW limb starting around 2024-09-21T10:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-09-21T16:53Z-23:09Z.The source is a narrow eruption from N25W80 at 2024-09-21T19:24Z. Ejecta and brightening seen in SDO AIA 304/131. Opening field lines and ejecta seen in SDO AIA 171. Faint dimming seen extending a bit further onto the disk at 19:44Z in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-22T19:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this event due to a data gap beginning at 2024-09-22T17:38Z. The source of this eruption is likely far sided, evidenced by field line movement seen beyond the NW limb in SDO AIA 171 around 2024-09-22T19:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-09-22T21:36Z. The source of this event is an M3.7 flare and filament eruption from S23E65 beginning at 2024-09-22T21:12Z. This flare is seen clearly in SDO AIA 94 and 131, and the filament material is seen best in SDO AIA 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, and GOES SUVI 284 along with post eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131. This filament appears to deflect towards the SW as it progresses as seen in GOES SUVI 304. A faint EUV wave seen in SDO AIA 193 also appears to expand more to the west.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery, and possibly obscured by the bright streamer. The potential source is opening field lines best seen in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-09-23T02:00Z, on the far side.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the south-southeast in SOHO C2/STEREO A COR2 imagery, overlapping with CME: 2024-09-23T20:48Z; possibly associated with a filament eruption at far southern latitudes seen best in SDO AIA 171 around 2024-09-24T01:48Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Disjoint CME seen to the east made up of a southeasterly, wider portion and a northeasterly, jet-like portion. Analysis focuses on the southeasterly portion. May be associated with a minor filament seen near 09:00Z in GOES SUVI 304/SDO AIA 304 or activity (moving and opening field lines) associated with active regions that are turning on to the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, fast eruption seen to the southwest in SOHO C2 and due west in STEREO A COR2, accompanied by a much wider, faint shock seen to the northwest in SOHO C2/C3. Appears to be associated with an eruption near AR3834 (S15W42) seen in SDO AIA 193/171 around 2024-09-29T05:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Lightbulb CME seen to the ENE in SOHO C2 and STEREO COR2A; associated with strongly opening magnetic field lines off/behind the NE limb seen best in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-09-29T08:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Flux rope CME seen to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3 and STEREO A COR2. A wider faint possibly shock-like feature is seen preceding the leading edge. Source is opening field lines beyond the E limb seen starting at 2024-09-30T02:45Z in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Follows CME: 2024-09-30T03:12Z in the field of view in the coronagraphs. The potential source is on the far side, and field line movement is seen beyond the east limb starting around 2024-10-01T05:21Z in SDO AIA 171 in ISWA.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow jet CME starting at the same time that the wider 2024-09-30T14:00Z CME more to the south. A possible source is a filament eruption with dimming around S55E40, as seen in AIA 193/304, however there is also another simultaneous eruption closer to S35E40 and an eruption and dimming centered at S65W01.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very asymmetric CME with two (or more) consecutive fronts (or possibly two overlapping CMEs). The source is a relatively minor eruption centered east of AR3834 - around ~S15W55 - with a very fast ejecta and dimming, as seen in the SW in AIA 193/304/171 at 15:57Z. STEREO A coronagraph imagery is available but very sporadic and poor quality b/c of the campaign mode.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-10-01T01:25Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely some ejecta  from AR 3834 (~S15W65) best seen in SDO AIA 193 that starts at 2024-10-01T00:37Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Developing CME with bulk seen predominantly to the southeast in early frames with a very faint, oval-shaped/asymmetric halo shock portion, associated with an X7.1-class flare and associated eruption from AR3842 (S17E18). Coronal signatures include an EUV wave and large-scale dimming in SDO AIA 171/193 with magnetic field line movement off the southern and southeast limbs and dimming of footpoints bridging the Active Region 3842 (S17E18) in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-03T08:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption centered at approx. N25E70 with liftoff beginning at approx. 2024-10-03T07:30Z as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. This filament erupted gradually, so there is a small amount of material seen preceding the main bulk of the CME from which the measurement was based.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2020-10-03T09:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption beginning at approx. 2024-10-03T09:19Z centered at approx. S30W15 with Southern deflection as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line movement is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Full halo CME observed in SOHO LASCO, and full halo directed slightly more eastward in STEREO COR2A. The source is an X9.0 flare from AR 3842 observed in many wavelengths but mainly SDO AIA 131, starting at 2024-10-03T12:08Z and peaking at T12:18Z. Also observed as an EUV wave and dimming in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284, with surface brightening in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large loop CME seen to the NE in SOHO/STEREO A embedded in outflow of halo CME: 2024-10-03T12:48Z. Associated with a filament eruption/snapping of magnetic field lines and surge seen best in SDO AIA/GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 171 near N30E60; the signature in SDO AIA 171 is particularly clear, as there is widely opening field line movement off the northeast limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME with an auriform presentation in both the outline of its bulk and shock, seen to the west in SOHO. Associated with a strong eruption from AR 13844 near S10W50 following an M6.7-class flare; an EUV wave is seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow, faint CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-03T22:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this CME is a minor filament eruption beginning at approximately 03/20:30Z centered at N35E50 as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 304, although the CME itself appears to be deflected towards the North. Minor field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193 as a result of this eruption.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-03T23:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this eruption, however faint field line movement can be seen along the NE limb in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 195 beginning at approximately 03/22:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and to the south in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be two eruptions in close proximity to each other in the SW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk. A dimming region possibly associated with a faint filament eruption is visible in SDO/AIA 193 starting around 2024-10-04T02:00Z in the SW near ARs 13842, 13839, and 13844 followed by moving/opening field lines visible in SDO/AIA 171 starting around 2024-10-04T03:00Z in the SW below ARs 13844, 13843, and 13836. The moving/opening field lines are largely visible heading to the west while the dimming appears to have some southern directionality. A third separate eruption from AR 13842 (an M4.0 flare) is likely associated with an overlapping CME feature. There is some uncertainty with this analysis due to the multiple eruptions in close proximity and timing to when the CME is first visible in coronagraph imagery. Both SOHO and STEREO A coronagraphs have data gaps during this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A southern CME with a somewhat uncertain front seen with some uncertainty overlapping with the earlier 2024-10-04T04:13Z CME and discernible mostly in difference imagery (not clearly seen in white light images). It is likely associated with the M4.0 flare from Active Region 3842 and the associated narrow, south-directed ejecta seen in AIA/SUVI 304 starting at 2024-10-04T05:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-04T10:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this CME is field line movement seen in the vicinity of S35W30 beginning at approximately 04/09:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-04T13:25Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is an eruption from the vicinity of AR 3844 (S15W37) beginning at approximately 04/12:30Z, although the CME itself appears to exhibit Southern deflection. Field line opening can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 171 along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A wide CME directly north in STEREO A coronagraph and a bit towards NNE in SOHO. There is a wider shock and a narrower brighter bulk. The shock looks like an asymmetric halo with additional part seen to the west in COR2A. There was no source found on the Earth-facing disk so the CME is likely backsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint and narrow outflow to the south and southwest.  The source has not been found - but there is a lot of activity in the SW quadrant which may be obscuring the source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in all coronagraphs. The source for this CME is uncertain, with no one distinct eruptive source and the entire southwest quadrant of SDO AIA 171 imagery observing broad field line movement from as early as 4Z this morning, likely due to the numerous active regions in the SW and SW limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and in STEREO COR2A white light imagery. The source is a thin jet-like filament eruption from on or just beyond the SW limb, best observed erupting at 2024-10-05T11:52Z in GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME to the northwest. Its source is likely the inconspicuous  opening of field lines in the northwest behind the limb seen in AIA 193/171 after 2024-10-05T19:05Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, narrow CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-06T04:48Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME appears to get overtaken by CME: 2024-10-06T06:12Z. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, however some very minor field line opening can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 at approx. 06/04:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, fast CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-06T05:48Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME is seen overlapping with CME: 2024-10-06T04:48Z and CME: 2024-10-06T06:12Z. There is no clear source seen on the disk as this CME is likely far sided, however minor field line movement can be seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint narrow outflow towards northwest. No clear source have been found for it, although there is a lot of activity in the western part of the disk today. The CME is not seen in STEREO imagery because of a large data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-10-07T03:48Z. Also seen in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is like some activity from the vicinity of AR 3841. There is some minor brightening and movement along field lines best seen in SDO AIA 171 starting about 1.5 hours prior to the CME appearing in C2.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide, bright CME seen to the southwest in SOHO C2/C3 seemingly composed of two or more overlapping loops with internal structure clearly visible and no cavity. Presence of very faint shock may possibly be seen due south in LASCO C2 running difference imagery and may begin to reveal itself to the north-northeast in late SOHO frames after 22:30Z, though disjoint from the main CME body. Associated with a sympathetic eruption resulting from the long duration X2.1/X1.0-class flares (AR3842) located farther behind the southwestern limb than where the X2.1 takes place (W60) as seen in SDO AIA 171 imagery; the CME appears to originate closer to the southwestern limb. Fast, widely opening field lines are also observed in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery for a few frames prior to a data gap starting at 2024-10-08T03:38Z. The source may be related to field line movement visible near the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery around 2024-10-08T00:40Z. Additionally, there are rising loops/possible post-eruptive arcades visible near the western limb around 01:00Z in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193 imagery which may also be related to this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, and is only visible in STEREO A COR2 after the leading edge is out of the field of view due to a data gap from 2024-10-08T03:38Z to 09:23Z. The source is a large filament eruption centered near S25W30 which begins to erupt, deflecting southward, around 2024-10-08T05:20Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at the time of the eruption, and post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 06:30Z in SDO AIA131, 171, and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and a few frames of STEREO A COR2 prior to a data gap starting at 2024-10-08T13:23Z. The source is likely far-sided, and seen as faint opening of field lines visible beyond the eastern limb in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 imagery starting around 2024-10-08T11:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Relatively narrow CME first seen in the East initially by STEREO A COR2, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. This event gets quickly overtaken by the X1.8-flare-associated halo 2024-10-09T02:12Z CME. The source of this event is possibly a more minor flare sympathetic to the X flare happening at the same time in Active Region 3853 (N20E63) with post-eruptive arcades or more minor opening field lines and slight dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284 originating from the vicinity of AR 3852 (S14E53). This more minor flare is not measurable since it coincides with the more intense flare.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, fast and complex-shaped full halo CME associated with the X1.8 class flare from the Active Region 13848 (N13W08). The CME has two lobes or fronts: the more western, slightly earlier one, and the more central on to the northeast. The flare is associated with the significant eruption marked by an EUV wave, a large area of deep dimming and by bright post-eruptive arcades. There also  seems to be a second eruption - the initially slowly developing eruption of a very large filament spanning from N20W15 to N15W55, to the northwest of the Active Region 3848, which starts prior to the X flare (~2024-10-08T22:19Z). This earlier eruption may be responsible for the more western lobe or front of this CME (which could possibly be a separate CME). The X-class flare could be potentially be responsible for the more central, northeastern lobe/front of this complex event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A clear, more western loop especially well seen in SOHO C2 (starting at 2024-10-09T02:12Z) and overlapping with a more central front associated with the Xclass flare. The start time was set to 02:23Z to distinguish it from the more central CME. The source of this more western front is likely the initially slowly developing eruption of a very large filament spanning from N20W15 to N15W55 to the northwest of Active Region 3848 which started prior to the X flare (~2024-10-08T22:19Z). This earlier eruption may be responsible for the more western lobe/front, while the flare could be responsible for the more central, northeastern front of this complex CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the W/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and a few frames of STEREO A COR2 after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 lasting from 2024-10-09T13:53Z to 2024-10-09T18:53Z. This CME is associated with the X1.4 flare from AR 13842 (S10W85) close to the SW limb. There is a narrow stream of ejecta visible in GOES SUVI 304 sourced from AR 13842 but deflected to the north and off the limb. In GOES SUVI 284, wide and fast opening field lines and departure of plasma from the W limb is visible. Very limited SDO AIA imagery for this event due to a shutter maneuver.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Halo CME first seen by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-10-01-T09:53Z, as well as in the East by SOHO LASCO C2/C3. There is no clear source seen for this event, however spacecraft triangulation (currently a 26 degree separation) reveals that this event likely originated from the far side, so a source eruption would be too far beyond the West limb to be visible.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast jet CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-10T18:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is clear opening field lines seen on or just beyond the NW limb (approx. N12W90) beginning at approx. 10/17:00Z in SDO AIA 193. This CME appears to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-11T12:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen on or just beyond the NW limb (footpoint at approx. S02W90 exhibiting Northern deflection) beginning at approx. 11/12:08Z as seen in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304. Opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME first seen in the SW by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-10-11T13:09Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. The source of this event is likely an area of opening field lines seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 193 beginning at approx. 11/12:45Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faintly visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and southwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely an eruption and opening of field lines visible beyond the southwest limb starting around 2024-10-12T10:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Large messy CME to the W/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is no clear source for this CME. There may be a wide shock feature associated with this CME that is faintly visible in white light and difference imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME slightly overlaps the CME at 2024-10-13T01:36Z. There is no clear source for this CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-13T17:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this event due to a data gap from 13/13:53Z to 13/22:53Z. There is no clear source seen for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright loop CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-14T00:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is an M3.4 class flare from AR 3848 (N17W78) peaking at 2024-10-14T00:17Z. This flare can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 131, along with opening field lines seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284, and STEREO A EUVI 195. A region of dimming is also visible to the North of this flare in SDO AIA 193 and STEREO A EUVI 195, which is indicative of a more Northern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-14T09:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a very long filament eruption beginning at approx. 14/08:00Z centered at approx. S30W70 as seen in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI and STEREO A EUVI 304. Opening field lines are visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195 along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 131, 193 and STEREO A EUVI 195.

note: CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-10-14T14:36Z, although this event likely began sooner but was not visible due to the cadence of SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. The source of this CME is an M1.8 class flare from AR 3848 (N17W86) peaking at 14/13:37Z. This flare is seen clearly in SDO AIA 131 along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in STEREO A EUVI 195.

note: CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. It overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-10-14T20:36Z. The source can be seen as brightening seen near AR 3848 just beyond the west limb. Field line movement is also seen in GOES SUVI 284.

note: CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Overlaps in the field of view with CME: 2024-10-14T17:36Z. The source is likely on the west limb, and some possible post-eruption brightening visible at 2024-10-14T21:27Z in SDO/AIA 304 near AR 3848.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible as a far-sided halo, primarily directed towards the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and northwest in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely far-sided as an opening of field lines is visible beyond the northeast limb starting around 2024-10-16T22:10Z in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery. The source may originate from former Active Region 13841, which was located around longitude -163 at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be an eruption from AR 3863 starting around 2024-10-19T09:00Z in SDO/AIA 304/171/211/94. Moving/opening field lines are visible in the SE of SDO/AIA 171, however it is not clear if these moving/opening field lines are associated with this eruption or another eruption that may be associated with the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2024-10-19T09:48Z to the SE.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint jet-like CME seen to the east-northeast predominantly in SOHO C2 imagery, but also in C3 imagery and STEREO A COR2; it appears with much more contrast in running difference imagery as opposed to white light imagery. Likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity as evidenced by triangulation, although a possible very low confidence source could be the post eruptive arcades on the earth facing disk around N27E70.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet CME seen to the northeast in SOHO C2 imagery shortly after the wide and bright 2024-20-21T09:24Z CME seen to the southeast, possibly overlapping. No major source eruptions were found for this CME, but the CME may be associated with a magnetic field line breaking off the eastern limb best seen in SDO AIA 193 observed near 2024-10-21T11:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The start time was difficult to determine as this event overlaps with preceding CME: 2024-10-21T13:48Z and CME: 2024-10-21T09:24Z. The source is likely far-sided and related to an opening of field lines and eruption visible beyond the southeast limb in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193 and 304 imagery starting around 2024-10-21T14:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Source is one of several instances of narrowly opening field lines and ejecta from either on or just beyond the E limb at latitude N00, but with northern deflection. Instances start as early as 2024-10-22T03:41Z (very diffuse outflow associated with that instance). There is a clearer instance of ejecta seen at 2024-10-22T07:30Z, which may possibly be the source for this CME, though the timing is rather early. It's also possible the source for this particular front is sourced from even further beyond the limb than we can see in UV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fan-shaped CME seen to the SE in all coronagraphs. The source appears to lie on or just beyond the SE limb, observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as rapidly moving field lines starting around 2024-10-22T17:01Z, and further evidenced on the far-side around E95 by triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME is blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. The source of this CME appears to be filament ejecta seen near S17E80 in SDO/AIA 304 starting around 2024-10-23T10:50Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and fast loop seen to the southeast as defined by its brighter leading edge similar in appearance to the 2024-10-23T11:12Z CME; no definitive source for this CME was found, but could be associated with moving field lines off the southeast limb as seen best in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow, faint CME observed to the southeast in STEREO A COR2 first during a SOHO data gap at which point SOHO later backfilled. Likely associated with diverging field lines seen off the southeast limb beginning around 14:45Z but becoming more apparent by 16:00Z best in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Partial halo CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is an X3.3 flare starting at 2024-10-24T03:30Z from AR 3869 (approx. S17E68). Brightening and post eruptive arcades are observed in SDO AIA 131/171/193/335, EUV wave seen in SDO AIA 193, and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193. The eruption is also seen from STEREO A EUV 195/304.

S40E90) as seen in SDO AIA 193.

note: Narrow jet CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery beginning at 2024-10-24T16:12Z. There is also no STEREO A COR2 imagery available due to a data gap from 13:23Z to 23:38Z. The source of this CME is some faint field line movement seen beyond the East limb in SDO AIA 171. This source seems to be obscured by the brightening of an active region which has just rotated onto the disk.

S11E85) exhibiting Northern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304.

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source may be an eruption on the disk from AR 3906 (S16E65) starting at 2024-11-23T09:37Z, based on field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284.

note: Faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap. The source appears to be an eruption from AR 13898/plage region 13893 in the SW based on SDO/AIA 131 and 193 starting around 2024-11-23T19:20Z. There are also moving/opening field lines visible along the limb in GOES SUVI 284 which may be associated with the eruption on the disk but could also indicate a far sided simultaneous eruption which could play into overlapping fronts seen with this CME to the SW.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-25T01:48Z. CME also seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is very faint in white light and is better seen in running difference imagery. The source of this CME is possibly some minor brightening and movement of plasma centered around N20E25 starting around 2024-11-25T00:27Z with some northward deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this CME. The front appears to be faint with a brighter core and possible h-alpha emission visible in C2 imagery. The source appears to be a filament eruption starting around 17Z beyond the SW limb in SDO/AIA 304. Associated moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 and 193 as well as in GOES SUVI 284 imagery
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-11-25T13:38Z to 2024-11-26T00:38Z. This CME partially overlaps with and follows in the path of preceding CME: 2024-11-25T18:00Z. The source for this event is unknown and likely far-sided, but may be related to the filament eruption visible just beyond the southwest limb in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery starting around 2024-11-25T17:00Z, which was associated with the aforementioned CME: 2024-11-25T18:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and possibly to the SE in STEREO A COR2 imagery following a data gap. The CME is likely associated with the M1.9 flare from AR 13091 as seen from SDO/AIA 131 and associated dimming in SDO/AIA 193 starting around 20:33Z. The dimming and associated EUV wave is seen moving out in all directions, most notably seen to the north, east, and south of the source location. This CME event overlaps with CMEs visible to the southwest which began around 2024-11-25T18:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-11-25T21:36Z. CME also seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 (partially obscured by pylon) and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely some activity involving ARs 3905 and 3906 staring around 2025-11-25T17:00Z that continues for a few hours. The movement and brightening is particularly visible in SDO AIA 304 and SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is limited imagery available for this CME in STEREO A COR2 data. The source appears to be a filament eruption on the eastern limb of SDO/AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-11-26T12:50Z. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in GOES SUVI 284 to the east with this eruption.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to the faintness of the CME. Source is a C3.5 flare from S20W72 (no AR) with peak time 2024-11-27T02:28Z and a narrow ribbon of ejecta similarly from about S20 near the SW limb seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-11-27T02:34Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very faint loop CME seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is very faint field line movement seen beyond the E limb in GOES SUVI 304/284 imagery, with a small amount of material (it did not fully escape and become ejecta) possibly associated with the eruption, starting around 2024-11-27T08:50Z. General field line movement and a very gradual 'thinning'/dimming/opening of field lines can be seen when toggling through GOES SUVI 284 imagery between 2024-11-27T08:00Z-14:00Z. GOES SUVI used for analysis; outage in SDO affecting all SDO data product timestamps starting at about 2024-11-26T23:52Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and one frame of STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a filament eruption  visible on or just beyond the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-11-27T19:26Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: No clear source has been found but around 2024-11-28T18:17Z in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284, there is an area of slight field lines movement close to the southeast limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast narrow jet to the southwest in both coronagraphs. No definitive source has been found on disk, however there may be a very minor movement of field lines on or close to the southwest limb around 2024-11-29T06Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME seen to the east-southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3; associated with a minor eruption near an equatorial active region near the eastern limb seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-11-2919:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is an eruption visible near the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 304 imagery starting around 2024-11-30T05:30Z which exhibits a clear southern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely an eruption visible on/near the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 284 and 304 imagery starting around 2024-11-30T10:40Z. An opening of field lines is visible over the eastern limb at this time in GOES SUVI 171 and 195 imagery as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-02T16:36Z. CME also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3. The CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is likely from beyond the SE limb at approximately -95 to -105 degrees longitude based on comparison with two previous CMEs (2024-12-01T22:00Z and 2024-12-02T07:12Z) that are very similar.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to overnight data gap which lasted from 2024-12-03T12:23Z to 2024-12-04T00:38Z. Source is likely a small jet-like eruption of material seen on or just beyond the NW limb (W90-W110) and at about N15 in GOES SUVI 304 (seen most clearly at later frame 2024-12-03T20:56Z) immediately following an on-limb filament eruption which had likely resulted in a preceding northwest CME: 2024-12-03T20:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the east/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely an eruption visible near the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery starting around 2024-12-05T00:30Z. A rising loop is visible over the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 171 and dimming is visible near the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 195 imagery around this time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast CME with protruding/faster nose seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO during a STEREO A COR2 data gap. Likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by moving field lines seen off the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with a fairly narrow shape but a type of "hook" at the end visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery (more easily identified in difference imagery). There isn't a clear source, however there is some moving/opening field lines along the SW of GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-06T23:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source appears to be a filament eruption near N10E60 as seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 06/01:15Z with associated moving/opening field lines visible in GOES SUVI 284 and dimming in GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Flux rope CME with an additional narrow portion on the southern edge that protrudes in front of the leading edge of the main flux rope shape seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption and X2.2 flare from AR 3912 (S07W52) which peaked at 2024-12-08T09:06Z. Dimming and opening field lines are seen starting at 2024-12-08T09:04Z in GOES SUVI 195/171 spanning from S20W50 to N05W50, with field line movement reaching as far as N20. Ejecta can also be seen in GOS SUVI 304 which can first be seen starting at 2024-12-08T09:24Z, but was likely initiated with the flare. Flare, dimming, and ejecta can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 at 2024-12-08T09:05Z and 09:15Z, respectively.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME associated with a thin, southward deflecting ejecta seen in the SSE in SUVI 304 around 02:52 and possibly associated with the C9.7 from AR 3922. This southward directed deflection of ejecta and CME is peculiar to today's events from Active Region 3922.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A relatively narrow CME associated withthe M6.4 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72), with a narrow southward-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2024-12-10T04:48Z. Because the sequence of flare/ejecta/CME events is very fast for this and the 2024-12-10T07:24Z CME the attribution to the linked flare is not absolutely certain.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is likely associated with the M1.4 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72) and is also associated with a thin southward-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in the southwest in GOES SUVI 304 imagery starting at 2024-12-10T07:16Z but best seen after 07:28Z. Because the sequence of flare/ejecta/CME events is very fast for this and the 2024-12-10T07:00Z CME (which is associated to the preceding M5.6 flare from the same active region), the exact attribution to the linked flare for these two CMEs is not absolutely certain.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME associated with M1.5 flare from AR 3922 (S18E72) and a narrow but eventually fan-shaped wide, south-deflecting ejecta from this AR seen in the southeast in SUVI 304/284 and on southeast limb in EUVI A 195 starting at 2024-12-10T11:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for the duration of this event. The potential source for this CME is an eruption with filament ejecta from AR 13920 (N22E24) starting around 2024-12-10T16:20Z in GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and possibly C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for the duration of this event. The source appears to be a filament ejecta eruption from AR 13920 (N22E28) starting around 2024-12-10T17:08Z as seen in GOES SUVI 304 with deflection to the NE.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event. The source appears to be an M1.6 class flare from AR 13922 (S18E70) with a sympathetic eruption to the west of this region starting around 2024-12-10T17:58Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 304, and 284. Moving/opening field lines are visible along the limb as well as a minor EUV wave to the south along the limb as seen in GOES SUVI 284 and 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery for the duration of this event. The source for this CME is possibly a small eruption from AR 13920 (N22E21) starting around 2024-12-10T20:58Z as seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME to the northeast, with messy, fuzzy, dimpled front. This CME islikely associated with minor activity in AR 13920 (N15E23).
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Another CME with an asymmetric shape in the "AR 3922 style". It is associated with the M1.9 flare from AR 3922 (S17E55), however the opening of field lines we see in in SUVI 284 seems to be further south from AR 3922. There is also opening of field lines in SUVI 171 closer to this AR.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME with fuzzy front to the northeast, with no clear front in SOHO LASCO C2 and likely associated with the M2.7 flare from Active Region 3920 (N22E18) and the narrow NNE ejecta seen at 2024-12-11T10:36 in SUVI 304 at the time.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Possible partial halo CME seen as two separate portions, a portion to the south and southeast visible in SOHO LASCO C2 as well as a portion to the northeast connected by a very faint front to the east. Also seen to the southwest in STEREO A COR2, suggesting it is far-sided. Likely associated with very faint, fluttering field line movement seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-12-11T12:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Far-sided halo CME with brighter bulk seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and also a fainter, torus-shaped shock with wider extent in the equatorial regions. Likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by expulsion and rapidly flickering field lines as seen off the south limb best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2024-12-11T21:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery following a data gap from 2024-12-12T15:36Z to 23:24Z. Following the data gap, the CME is visible well into the SOHO LASCO C2/C3 field of view, so the start time is likely earlier than the time stated. This event is visible in STEREO A COR2 after a data gap ending at 2024-12-13T00:53Z for only a few frames. The source is a slow-rising loop visible near or slightly beyond the southwest limb which erupts around 2024-12-12T23:00Z as seen in GOES SUVI 131, 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb at this time in GOES SUVI 171 and 195 imagery as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery following a data gap from 2024-12-12T15:36Z to 23:24Z. Following the data gap, the CME is visible into the SOHO LASCO C2/C3 field of view, so the start time is likely a bit earlier than the time stated. This event is visible in STEREO A COR2 after a data gap ending at 2024-12-13T00:53Z for only a few frames. The source is an eruption visible from beyond the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 304 imagery starting around 2024-12-12T23:16Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the south/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Partially overlaps in the field of view of the coronagraphs with CME: 2024-12-13T02:48Z. The source is likely an M1.0 flare starting at 2024-12-13T03:11Z from AR 3922 (S18E37) with dimming, opening field lines best seen in GOES SUVI 195/284 as well as an ejecta of material in GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The potential source is a filament eruption centered around S35E30 with liftoff starting around 2024-12-13T06:48Z as best seen in GOES SUVI 304. The eruption is also visible in STEREO A 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Wide CME seen predominantly to the south in SOHO LASCO imagery during a STEREO A data gap. May be potentially associated with an M1.0 flare from AR 3922 starting at 2024-12-13T14:15Z, but there is no clear eruption of material leading to a CME associated with it. There is some faint dimming seen in GOES SUVI 284 at 14:26Z, close in time to when this was in the coronagraphs. Initial analysis suggests this eruption originates from the far-side, but triangulation with STEREO A data is probably necessary to confirm front-sidedness.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast, thin CME seen to the SSE in all coronagraphs. The source appears to be a small filament eruption from AR 3922 (S16W24), best observed in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2024-12-14T01:28Z, which then deflects sharply southward after erupting. This eruption is notably close to the CME start time, but it is the best candidate and the filament shape in GOES SUVI aligns visually with the coronagraph signature.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the SW only in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO COR2A was available at this time but this CME isn't observed there. The source is likely near/south of Active Region 3916 decayed to a plage, with a narrow filament ejecta observed in GOES SUVI 304 around S20W70 starting around 2024-12-14T02:36Z. The CME precedes a similarly shaped, brighter and more distinct 2024-12-14T05:36Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME likely associated with minor flare and filament eruption seen around ~2024-12-14T05:12 near/south of Active Region 3916 decayed to a plage (~S15W69) or alternatively a less certain eruption of very long filament along longitude ~S25 centered around 35-40 deg longitude, maybe seen erupting in SUVI 304/284 (but it is more likely that the matter fell back). The CME is preceded by a similarly shaped even fainter 2024-12-14T04:00Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast CME to the west, the beginning of which is covered by a data gap in SOHO. Its source was hard to identify since there are multiple eruption close to SW limb near this time, as well as a faint movement of field lines likely beyond the W limb in SUVI 171/195 at 2024-12-15T00:50Z. In EUVI A 195 near the west limb (in STEREO) there are post-eruptive arcades seen at ~2024-12-15T01:05Z after the long data gap. The very approximate location of this  source in STEREO A is ~110 degrees.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint partial halo CME first seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2024-12-15T04:23Z, as well as faintly in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. This CME overlaps with previous CME: 2024-12-15T01:25Z, making the front difficult to track in SOHO LASCO. The source of this event appears to be an area of dimming centered near AR 3924 (S19W18) as seen GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME with core visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap beginning at 15/11:38Z in STEREO A COR2 imagery for this CME. The CME has a faint halo shock visible in later frames. The source appears to be far sided with wide moving/opening field lines to the SE in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2024-12-15T14:19Z. A portion of the front appears to be moving faster than the rest of the CME which may be indicative of an overlapping CME. However, due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints and lack of a separately identifiable source, this feature was excluded in the measurement of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen to the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-12-15T20:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 15/11:38Z to 16/00:23Z. The source of this event appears to be an area of field line movement seen along the SE limb (approx. S15E90) as seen in GOES SUVI 195 and 284
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Minor and relatively faint CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and not seen well in STEREO A COR2 data. Likely associated with moving field lines from an active region rotating onto the Earth-facing disk at perhaps a longitude between -80 and -90 degrees, as seen in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME faintly visible to the southwest in STEREO A COR2. This CME not was clearly seen in any available SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source was also not found. The CME fades away after a few frames of STEREO A COR2 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast, farsided halo CME in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not seen in STEREO A COR2 in real time due to a data gap starting at 2024-12-17T11:38Z. Faint, wide field line movement is seen on the southwest limb in GOES SUVI 284 at 2024-12-17T15:59Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-18T06:36Z. Also visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C3 and in white light only to the NW in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely an eruption from south of AR 3920 (N12W90) starting around 2024-12-18T05:56Z in GOES SUVI 284. Another source possibility is a spot of activity a few degrees north (~N16W85) that also "erupted" around 2024-12-18T05:36Z. Both source candidates are bright in GOES SUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is very likely the eruption of a small filament starting around 2024-12-18T14:49Z as seen in GOES SUVI 304, which was seen on the disk spanning approx. S05W70 to S22W65, near Active Region 3924 (S20W65). Part of this CME is not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2024-12-18T11:38Z to 2024-12-18T16:36Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the NE is SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2024-12-19T01:25Z. Also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is very faint in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is likely a large rising loop of field lines seen from beyond the NE limb in GOES SUVI 284, first noticeable starting at 2024-12-19T00:39Z. There is some minor influence seen in the NE quadrant of the Earth-facing disk, but this eruption appears much more likely to be far-sided. A far-sided source is also consistent with measurements.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Halo CME first seen in STEREO A COR2 at 2024-12-19T17:53Z. The bulk of the CME is to the SW. This CME is also seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This start time was chosen based on when the CME was first seen in available imagery at the time of analysis, but the actual start time is earlier. The source of this CME is most likely far-sided. There are no good source candidates on the Earth-facing disk, and coronal signatures from beyond the SW limb suggest a far-sided source.  In GOES SUVI 284, there is some flickering in the farthest out field lines over the SW limb across most of the SW quadrant first seen at about 2024-12-19T16:19Z. There is also some very faint ejecta seen from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting about 2024-12-19T16:21Z. Measurements are consistent with a far-sided source. This CME also overlaps with a prior filament eruption to the SW.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow jet seen to the WSW in C2/C3/COR2A, potentially associated with a visible filament eruption seen near 2024-12-20T22:30Z seen in the southwest portion of the disk. Based on the measurement, the filament near S40W35 seems to be better the source candidate.
