The source for this CME is uncertain, as it appears to form early in the LASCO C2 FOV rather than moving out from the occulting disk, but there are two potential candidates if it does start on-disk. A small filament eruption from AR 3933 (~S07W55) starting at 2024-12-28T07:56Z in GOES SUVI 195/304 fits the measured longitude well but not latitude, and there is also field line movement beginning on the NW limb (~N18) around 2024-12-28T08:08Z in GOES SUVI 195 that doesn't fit longitude but is a more northward latitude. Widely opening field lines, brightening, and ejection of material can be seen in GOES SUVI 131/171/195/211/304 starting at about 2025-01-07T22:10Z. The tops of post-eruptive arcades can be seen emerging from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 171 starting at about 2025-01-07T23:48Z. There is some uncertainty in the exact location of this eruption since this is not directly on the disk, but it is very likely associated with Active Region 13939 which is estimated to have been located at roughly S17W99 at the peak time of the flare [2025-01-07T23:05Z].

note: Minor, narrow CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2 and presumably to the south in STEREO A COR2A, seemingly associated with a far-sided minor filament eruption seen around 18:00Z to the southeast in GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 304. Triangulation suggests the CME originates from near a longitude of -145 degrees.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SE fully in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and to the S/SW potentially as a partial halo in STEREO COR2A after 2025-02-06T05:09Z, with the CME front already at the edge of its FOV when its beacon data downlink resumes. Due to this data gap timing in STEREO COR2A, the CME is observed in white light imagery but unresolvable in running difference imagery. Observed as a rapid snapping open and dimming of field lines over the SE limb centered ~S28, best observed in SDO AIA 171/193 around 2025-02-06T02:31Z and GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-02-06T02:34Z. Also observed in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304 as some filament ejecta. The far-sided nature of this CME is also corroborated via fitting in swpc_cat and the lack of an on-disk signature accompanying the field line movement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright filament eruption to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is a filament eruption occurring on/beyond the NW limb as viewed from SDO AIA and GOES SUVI, first seen on the NW limb as viewed from STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-02-06T10:15Z, confirmed to be separate from the M7.6 flare (AR 13981) that occurred on the earth-facing disk at this same time. Also observed starting around 2025-02-06T10:36Z in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304, launching more explosively around 2025-02-06T11:32Z. Also seen well as the filament ejecta and field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, outflow like CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-06T15:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-02-06T15:23Z to 2025-02-07T02:53Z. The source of this event is faint field line movement seen along the South limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright lightbulb CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-07T03:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen along the SE limb in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 during a STEREO A data gap; the CME is likely associated with a far-sided eruption occurring behind the southeastern limb, as evidenced best by moving field lines seen off the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not visible in SDO AIA imagery, but an eruption can be seen just on or beyond the southwest limb in STEREO A EUV 304 imagery starting at 2025-02-08T12:45Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint CME to the northwest only seen in several SOHO LASCO C2 images and largely obscured by the pylon in C3 imagery. The CME is fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A imagery. No clear coronal signatures have been found for this CME, although some very minor activity is going on in the northwest, possibly from AR 13978 (N14W77).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A super faint jet to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in STEREO A COR2 (and in difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2) and only seen in 2-3 early timestamps in SOHO LASCO C3 because of extreme faintness of this event. No source was found on the Earth-facing disk, so it is likely a farsided event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption and associated C5.8 flare located at N15E75. Opening field lines, a rising loop, and ejecta are seen starting at 2025-02-11T06:12Z in SDO AIA 193/171/304/131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is best observed in SDO AIA 304 as a filament eruption on the eastern limb around S10E90, beginning around 2025-02-11T17:48Z and erupting more explosively around 2025-02-11T18:04Z. Also observed as field line opening in SDO AIA 171/193, and a C7.2 flare peaking at 2025-02-11T18:25Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-12T02:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is not entirely clear. However, a region of brightening is visible in SDO AIA 94 located at approx. N10E70 beginning at approx. 12/02:24Z. A 2-coronagraph measurement indicates that the CME likely resulted from activity in this area, however, due to the timing, this brightening may be post-eruptive arcades from an eruption that is not as visible opposed to the actual source of the CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 20254-02-12T21:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-02-12T10:38Z to 2025-02-13T03:23Z. There is no clear source seen for this event, aside from general field line movement seen along the East limb in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, narrow CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-13T01:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-02-12T10:38Z to 2025-02-13T03:23Z. There is no clear source seen for this event aside from general field line movement along the NE limb seen in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. It is very faint with a diffuse front. The potential source of this CME is a dimming centered around S07W10 just East of AR13992 as seen in SDO/AIA 193 and 211 starting around 2025-02-13T14:00Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this CME due to a data gap beginning at 2025-02-13T17:09Z. The source of this CME is likely a filament eruption visible in SDO/AIA 304 and 171 just beyond the SE limb starting around 2025-02-13T16:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow, faint CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 during a STEREO A data gap. Likely associated with a small filament eruption starting around 2025-02-13T20:00Z in the NE on Earth-facing disk around N20W45 (seen best in SDO AIA 193).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Wide, faint CME seen primarily to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 which appears to be associated with a C6.6-class flare from Active Region 13994 and subsequent eruption seen best in SDO AIA 094 and SDO AIA 304 with notable deflection to the east. Despite the overall weak eruptive signature, triangulation strongly suggests that the eruption is associated with front-sided activity bounded by longitudes -25 to -45.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Jet CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2A likely associated with a minor eruption from Active Region 13991 (S12E36), as evidenced by an eruptive signature taking place in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 during a STEREO A data gap; the CME is possibly associated with a minor eruption from Active Region 13994 located near S21W00 as seen in SDO AIA 94, 304, though it isn't definitive where the eruption originates. Triangulation is not currently possible due to a STA COR2 data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only, STEREO COR2A beacon data entirely misses this event. Partially overlaps with CME 2025-02-14T22:00Z to the SE. The source for this CME is likely an area of the disk ~N14E33 which brightens and releases some filament material to the NE starting around 2025-02-14T20:58Z, best observed in SDO AIA 171/193/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Fast CME seen  to the NE in both coronagraphs, faint in SOHO LASCO and bright in STEREO A COR2. In STEREO A it is only seen after the nighttime data gap ends. Its source is likely a significant filament eruption centered around N11E31, seen starting around 2025-02-15T00:56Z in GOES SUVI 304 and in SDO AIA 304, but also seen as small area brightening in SDO AIA 193. There is also a lower class C flare associated with it.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME with a high southern latitude, seen to the west in STEREO A COR2 and almost exactly to the south in SOHO LASCO, indicating a backsided source. Coronal signatures include a huge prominence seen directly to the south in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-02-12:56Z and originating behind the south limb, and also seen as an extensive movement of matter/field lines to the south and southeast in GOES SUVI 284, also likely happening behind the southern limb. Coronal signatures are almost not seen in SDO AIA, except for minimal movement of ejecta seen in AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The CME is partially obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. No visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-02-15T17:09Z. The source is an eruption from Active Region 13983 (approx. N06W90) starting at 2025-02-15T19:22Z. Brightening and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284. The eruption is also visible in SDO AIA 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. There is a data gap in STEREO A COR2 during this event. The source appears to be a filament eruption beyond the NE limb starting around 2025-02-19T18:47Z as seen in SDO/AIA 304, 171, 131, 195, and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Loop CME overlapping overlaps CME 2025-02-20T00:36Z which begins as a very narrow event but evolves as a wider event with time, seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Likely associated with far-sided activity based on its association with several far-sided events throughout the day, though the source is not known.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow CME seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the southeast in STEREO A COR2 in association with a large scale filament eruption taking place near S45E70, seen best in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304. Liftoff starts around 2025-02-20T04:50Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Wide CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 composed of a brighter bulk to the south and possibly a separate portion just to the north. Likely associated with large scale dimming taking place near S10E60 seen best in GOES SUVI 195 and SDO AIA 193 starting at 2025-02-20T09:28Z. Triangulation of the leading edge measures a bit closer to the Earth-Sun line than anticipated, and this may be due to a simultaneous eruption occurring near center disk around 2025-02-20T11:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: The first in a series of three overlapping CMEs. This CME is visible to the W/slightly NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and similarly to the W/slightly NW in STEREO A COR2. The leading edge is more faint and narrow than those of the other subsequent CMEs. The source of this CME is part of a complex eruption taking place on the NW limb in SDO imagery. As early as 2025-02-20T18:00Z in SDO AIA 193, a loop over the NW limb can be seen beginning to slowly rise, located above or near some destabilizing filament material hovering above on the NW limb in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The second in a series of three overlapping CMEs. This CME is visible to the W/slightly NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and similarly to the W/slightly NW in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is part of a complex eruption taking place on the NW limb in SDO imagery. At 2025-02-21T09:24Z, a wide loop snaps open in SDO AIA 171/193, and some filamentary material rapidly rises high in the corona but fails to escape solar gravitational forces, remaining suspended in the corona for a few hours. The wide loop that snapped open is a candidate source for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The third in a series of three overlapping CMEs. This bright flux rope CME is visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the NW in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is part of a complex eruption taking place on the NW limb in SDO imagery. Around 2025-02-21T11:27Z, suspended filament material finally ejects outward in SDO AIA 171/193/304. A large post-eruptive arcade on the NW limb also begins around 2025-02-21T11:27Z, expanding from N10->N35 on/just inside the NW limb. This filament eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery, showing post-eruptive arcades and brightening stretching from N35W60 to N15W90, near AR 3989 (~N20W85) [30 degrees have been added to all STEREO A EUVI longitudes to translate to Earth-facing disk coordinates].
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A loop CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO but partially obscured by pylon in C3 and covered by the 202-02-21T15:53Z-2025-02-22T03:23Z gap in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a minor activity close to the NW limb (possibly in AR 3989 located at N19W90 at the time on in AR 4001 that is also close to the NW limb), manifesting as the opening/movement of field lines on/close to the NW limb that is seen in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 284 EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the northwest associated with an M4.9-class flare from AR 14001 which peaked at 2025-02-23T02:13Z at N25W82. Beginning around 2025-02-23T02:09Z, wide opening field lines and small post-eruptive arcades are observed in SDO AIA 171/193. First of three CMEs emanating from this area including the faster 02:48Z CME and slower/outflow-related 03:24Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very fast and thin CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 out ahead of the 2025-02-23T03:24Z CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery; the source is likely associated with an M4.9-class flare from AR 4001 which peaked at 2025-02-23T02:13Z at N25W82 (14001). Beginning around 2025-02-23T02:09Z, wide opening field lines and small post-eruptive arcade are seen in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Likely outflow associated with CME: 2025-02-23T02:36Z, an eruption associated with an M4.9-class flare from AR 14001 which peaked at 2025-02-23T02:13Z at N25W82. Beginning around 2025-02-23T02:09Z, wide opening field lines and small post-eruptive arcade are observed in SDO AIA 171/193. Triangulation with STEREO Ahead suggests the eruption is sourced around W55 but this is not supported by EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow jet CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2; the source may be loose field line movement over AR 4004 (S15E65 at this time) starting around 2025-02-23T10:15Z in SDO AIA 193 but confidence is low.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very wide CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 during a STEREO A COR2A data gap composed with a well-defined western and southwestern leading edge and not-as-defined northern leading edge, associated with an X2.0-class flare and subsequent eruption from AR 14001 (N25W87) as evidenced by strong brightening in SDO AIA 131 and quickly separating field lines seen in SDO AIA 193, 171 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very faint CME to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. Not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be moving/opening field lines along the southern limb as seen in SDO/AIA 193 starting around 2025-02-24T00:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, wide CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. Source is seen in SDO AIA 171/193/211 as field line movement beginning around 2025-02-24T04:09Z over the NW limb, with an EUV wave at 2025-02-24T15:18Z, and as a filament liftoff starting around 2025-02-24T05:06Z. The source is better seen in STEREO A EUVI with the filament on/just inside the west limb as viewed from STEREO A. At 2025-02-24T05:15Z, STEREO A was located 30.297 degrees from Earth, putting its west limb around W120.3. Here in STEREO A EUVI 304, the filament can be seen slowly rising starting at 2025-02-24T03:15Z->T5:15Z, and ejecting by the next timestamp at T05:45Z. A post-eruptive arcade follows in STEREO A EUVI 195/304. The source could be, or be near, old AR 3989, which rotated off the west limb on 2025-02-21 and would be located approximately W115-W125.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the WNW is SOHO LASCO C2. CME is also seen as a partial halo mostly to the NW in STEREO A COR2 but is obscured by the pylon is SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is very difficult to distinguish from the previous CME in white light imagery. The source is most likely associated with an M3.3 flare from AR 14000 (N17W21) that peaked at 2025-02-24T07:02Z. The flare and a region of dimming projected south of the flare are seen across SDO AIA and GOES SUVI wavelengths but are best seen in SDO AIA 193. There also appears to be some western deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3, but not in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2025-02-24T20:23Z. The source of this CME is likely associated with an eruption visible beyond the SW limb starting around 2025-02-24T20:27Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131 with associated brightening, moving/opening field lines, and an EUV wave best seen in SDO/AIA 211. Following the eruption, there were very notably post-eruptive arcades which were associated with a long duration, occulted M3.9 flare from former AR 13990 (S13W120) that peaked at 2024-02-24T23:02Z. The very beginning of the flare can be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 on the W limb in the last frame (2025-02-24T20:35Z) prior to the end of a downlink period. Additionally, very fast opening field lines are visible from beyond the W limb starting around 2025-02-24T20:24Z in SDO/AIA 193, SDO/AIA 171, GOES SUVI 195, and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME first seen in the SW by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-02-25T12:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. The beginning frames of this event in SOHO LASCO are obscured by a data gap from 25/11:12Z to 25/13:39Z. The source of this CME is an M3.6 flare from AR 3998 (S15W55) as seen in SDO AIA 131. Opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 94, 171 and 193, along with an area of dimming seen in SDO AIA 94, 193, 211 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only, missed in STEREO COR2A due to a data gap. The CME travels into the pylon in C3 hindering visibility in white light and running difference imagery. The source is observed as a field line loop breaking over the NW limb around 2025-02-25T14:18Z in SDO AIA 171/193, potentially from old AR 4001 which rotated over the NW limb on 2025-02-24.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-26T06:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a filament eruption centered at approx. S10W25 exhibiting a strong Westward deflection. This filament is visible in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304, along with dimming and post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 193 and STEREO A EUVI 195. A large North-South configured coronal hole is visible approximately 10 degrees to the East of the eruptive source. This coronal hole may cause deflection or acceleration of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is a filament eruption seen near S30W70 in SDO/AIA, STEREO A EUVI and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-02-26T14:00Z. There is strong southern deflection of the eruption, likely due to the large coronal holes to the north and east of the source location. Field line opening is also visible in SDO/AIA 171, 193, and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the W/SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in a few frames of STEREO A COR2 imagery before a data gap beginning around 2025-02-26T19:00Z. The exact start time of this CME is unclear due to the overlap with the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-02-26T15:00Z. The possible source of this CME is a filament eruption beginning around 2025-02-26T11:15Z in STEREO A EUVI, GOES SUVI, and SDO/AIA 304 imagery near ~S15W90+. A slow rising loop is visible in GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery along the W/SW limb starting around 2025-02-26T12:00Z which may have been fully released from the lower/middle corona when the filament eruption associated with the overlapping CME to the SW occurred.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in limited imagery in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The CME exhibits an initial faint, diffuse front with a brighter portion (more clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery) that appears to be the bulk of the CME. The source appears to be a possible filament eruption stretching along the eastern side of the large N-S oriented coronal hole located near central meridian. Brightening is visible in SDO/AIA and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-02-26T14:16Z. Associated dimming and post-eruptive arcades are visible in SDO/AIA 195 and GOES SUVI 284. Deflection is likely for this CME due to the large coronal holes to the west of the source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint and wide loop CME first seen to the NW in STEREO A COR2 and seen after a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2. The leading edge is nearly fully obstructed by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. Source is likely opening loops and field line movement seen just beyond the (STEREO A) northwest limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery, starting around 2025-02-27T06:25Z and located at about N20W120 (Earth-facing disk coordinates).
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, partial halo to halo CME visible in the W/NW of SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a far-sided filament eruption visible along the NW limb of STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 starting around 2025-02-28T16:45Z. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 starting around 2025-02-28T17:35Z. Moving/opening field lines and an EUV wave is visible in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-02-28T17:00Z. The source is suspected to be from AR 13993 (~N15W125) based on available STEREO A EUVI data. Note that there was a simultaneous, much less significant, eruption centered at (~W01W60) at the time of the far-sided eruption associated with this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-28T16:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a C5.2 flare and jet-like eruption from Active Region 4006 (N18W02), exhibiting a very strong Northeastern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. This CME partially overlaps and is obscured by CME: 2025-02-28T17:12Z in later frames.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2 with fainter loops following shortly behind. Brightening is visible in SDO/AIA, GOES SUVI, and STEREO A EUVI 304. Dimming, moving/opening field lines, and post-eruptive arcades are best visible in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO/AIA 193.

note: Narrow faint jet to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in running difference imagery. Its source is likely a C2.4 class flare (and a super minor ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 304) from AR 4011 (S18E58) starting at 2025-03-02T03:37Z.

note: Faintest of the 3 consecutive narrow jets from AR 4011 this morning. Its source is likely the C1.2 flare from AR 4011 (S18E57) starting at 2025-03-02T05:46Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint narrow CME to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in running difference imagery.  Its source is likely the C2.7 flare and a minor eruption in AR 4011 (S18E54) seen in SDO AIA 131, 304 and GOES SUVI 304, 284 and on SE limb in EUVI A 195 at 2025-03-02T09:57Z. Note that there also seems to be an even more minor eruption off the SW limb at the same time seen in SDO AIA 304/ GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright heart-shaped CME to the northwest in both coronagraphs. No source has been found on the Earth-facing disk, but there is a faint flicker/movement of field lines far behind the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171 seen most clearly at 2025-03-02T11:09Z but really faintly seen as early as 2025-03-02T10:15Z, and also possibly seen as a faint/indistinct movement beyond the northwest limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 at 2025-03-02T10:35Z. Most likely this is a backsided CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the SSE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-03T17:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a date gap 03/14:23Z to 03/21:38Z. The source of this event may be related to faint field line movement visible over the S/SE limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery starting around 2025-03-03T17:00Z
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME visible to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The potential source of this CME is a filament eruption centered near S27E45 (below active regions 14012 and 14011) starting around 2025-03-04T03:20Z as seen in SDO/AIA 304. Associated moving/opening field lines and possible EUV wave visible to the south and south west towards the south pole as seen in SDO/AIA 193 indicating southern deflection, likely due to the coronal hole located N/NE of the source location. Associated brightening and dimming are also visible in SDO/AIA 131, 304, and 193 in the area of the source with additional dimming visible further south closer to the south pole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME partially overlaps the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-04T03:48Z. The potential source for this CME is a filament eruption near S42W95 with associated moving/opening field lines visible along the SW limb in SDO/AIA 304 and 171 starting around 2025-03-04T03:51Z. There appears to be southward deflection possibly due to coronal holes in the vicinity of the source location. The coronal holes and the eruptions deflection are more clearly seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME with diffuse front visible along streamer to the south in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The potential source is a filament eruption centered around S25E42 (below ARs 14012 and 14011) visible in SDO/AIA 304 starting around 2025-03-04T09:30Z. Brightening and dimming are also visible in SDO/AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely an eruption visible on/near the southwest limb starting around 2025-03-04T18:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the west/northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-04T19:38Z. The source is likely related to an eruption visible near the northwest limb (centered near ~N15W80) starting around 2025-03-04T21:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A faint CME with a fuzzy front to the northeast, closely followed by a second, brighter, front, better seen in SOHO than in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. There is a super faint wider front that might indicate a shock front. No source has been found for this CME, so it is likely far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint flux rope CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2, then seen as an extremely faint feature to the SE in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a set of loops/flux rope seen lifting off from on or just beyond the southeast limb (loop spans approx. S20-S25 and E110-E90) starting at about 2025-03-05T03:34Z in SDO AIA 171 imagery. Post-eruptive arcades appear several hours later and seemingly from the same location starting at about 2025-03-05T06:36Z in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and briefly in STEREO COR2A before a data gap begins at 2025-03-05T11:53Z. The source is a small filament which spanned roughly N28W55->N28W70 (centered N28W62) near AR 14006 (N18W70) at 2025-03-05T10:09Z just before erupting. The eruption is best seen in SDO AIA 304 as the filament material brightening and lifting off, and also observed in SDO AIA 171 as field line movement to the NW.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow and faint jet CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is a faint and narrow loop / opening field line movement can be seen in GOES SUVI 284 off the NE limb, first distinguishable at 2025-03-06T03:00Z when the loop is already near the edge of the SUVI 284 field of view. There are two candidates for the origin of this loop: 1) a very small instance of brightening at 2025-03-06T02:58Z from AR 4017 (S05E56), or 2) from just beyond the NE limb, likely located near the northernmost footpoint of the arc of field lines visible on the NE limb in UV imagery which turns into the streamer visible to the NE in coronagraph imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen to the SSE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-07T02:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event in an eruption centered at approx. S30E10 beginning at approx. 07/01:15Z as seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Dimming is also visible in SDO AIA 193 exhibiting a strong Southern deflection. A larger coronal hole is visible to the North of this eruption sight in SDO AIA 211, which may be contributing to the Southern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Loop CME seen to the SW in both SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is an M1.6 flare and eruption from AR 4016 (S26E10). Dimming with southward deflection is seen starting at 2025-03-07T20:59Z in SDO AIA 193 and spans about 10 degrees radially around AR 4016 i.e. from S15 to S35 and from E20 to E00. Opening field lines with some southward deflection can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 as well. Post-eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304, including some from nearby AR 4012 (S13W06) starting at 2025-03-07T21:04Z. An EUV wave is seen propagating southward from AR 4016 in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This narrow on-disk CME is seen as a faint flux rope due south in SOHO LASCO C2 and simultaneously as a faint loop to the southeast in STEREO A COR2, which is currently 30 degrees to the west of SOHO LASCO. The source is a subtle eruption from AR 4012 (S20W00) starting at 2025-03-07T21:35Z, seen as dimming, brightening, and field line opening in SDO AIA 193 and 171, as well as GOES SUVI 284 and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow and fast CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery associated with a point source eruption from Active Region 14011 (S14W29) seen erupting around 2025-03-08T14:45Z in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 284. The active region footpoint is seen to have a small brightening during the eruption followed by a dark jet of plasma material leaving to the southwest with some deflection to the west.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, narrow, somewhat asymmetrical CME to the northeast, with a protruding pointy nose. Source: minor eruption/prominence on/behind the northeast limb seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-03-08T22:10Z and as very minor movement of field lines behind the NE limb in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-09T11:53Z. The source is likely related to an eruption, which exhibits northern deflection, visible on or slightly beyond the northeast limb (~N30E90) starting around 2025-03-03T12:25Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This event is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and south in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption from Active Region 14012 (S15W40) starting around 2025-03-10T03:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. The source eruption exhibits a southeast deflection, suggesting that the CME parameters may measure southeast of the on-disk source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faint but visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery before the leading edge becomes too diffuse to observe. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and relatively narrow CME to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The leading edge appears slightly brighter in STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO. The source is opening field lines seen starting at 2025-03-11T03:35Z located on or just beyond the W limb as seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 (W120-130 from SDO AIA perspective) and spanning approximately N00 to S10 in latitude, although the eruption likely extends to farther beyond the limb. Field line movement and the disappearance of a small loop of material can be seen from the same location in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery between the 2025-03-11T03:45Z and 2025-03-11T04:45Z frames.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and more directed towards the north in STEREO Ahead COR2 imagery composed of a fainter, faster shock. No sources on the Earth-facing disk in EUV imagery seem to be associated with this event, so the CME is likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap; it appears similar in appearance to the CME: 2025-03-11T18:24Z which was determined to likely be far-sided. Few, if any sources on the Earth-facing disk suggest that this CME occurs with eruptive activity on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bulbous jet-like CME to northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO, similar to the 2025-03-11T23:24Z CME. No clear source was found on disk but there are some movements of field lines behind the limb in the NE after 05Z in AIA 193. The CME is likely farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 composed of a bright narrow bulk and a fainter shock extending to the north and west relative to the bulk. The source is a minor eruption from near Active Region 4020 (N20E13) with northern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 193, 171, 304 as early as 2025-03-13T16:49Z; darkening in SDO AIA 193, brightening in SDO AIA 304 and the appearance of a breaking loop in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and east-northeast in STEREO A COR2A composed of a bright narrow bulk extending to the northeast and second more minor outflow seen more to the north. The source may be associated with a minor eruption seen near the eastern limb around E80 as early as 2025-03-14T02:00Z; mostly in GOES SUVI 284 imagery, or the eruption may be far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is additional wide and subtle field line movement seen on and very likely extending beyond the SW limb, best seen in STEREO A EUVI 193, and likely a direct consequence of or sympathetic eruption to a filament eruption seen starting at to lift off the southwest limb at 2025-03-15T04:09Z as seen in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:36Z, whose source is the filament eruption on the southwest limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note:
One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption on the southwest limb, spanning from about S25W85 to S10W120 with southward deflection seen as it erupts in SDO AIA and STEREO-A EUV imagery. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:24Z, whose source is nearly simultaneous and in close proximity. 

Filamentary material is seen starting to lift off at 2025-03-15T04:09Z in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. Post-eruptive arcades can be seen in SDO AIA 193 and 171 starting at 2025-03-15T06:28Z and lasting for multiple hours. Bright material can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 as well. This eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 193 imagery, which has frames available after a data gap ending at 2025-03-15T03:45Z and reveals liftoff of material starting with the next frame with timestamp 2025-03-15T04:15Z. With STEREO A currently at a HEEQ longitude of 31, this vantage point reveals that there was a filament eruption and a separate but sympathetic rising loop directly next to the filament, which altogether extended from approximately S25W80 to S10W121 (coordinates listed as would be seen by SDO. STEREO A is currently at a HEEQ longitude of +31 degrees).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow faint jet seen to the northeast in a couple of early timestamps in SOHO LASCO C2. Not seen in STEREO A COR2. A possible source is a narrow bright ejecta on/behind the east limb in AIA 304 around 2025-03-15T18:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Complex-shaped, somewhat pointy-nosed and possibly partial halo CME to the southwest, seen the brightest in STEREO A COR2. Its source is behind the SW limb (both in SDO and in STEREO A) and likely associated with Active Region 4012 (now at approximately W125) which was fairly complex when it was on the Earth-facing disk; its coronal signatures are fast-opening field lines behind the SW limb in both EUV imagers starting at 2025-03-16T00:32Z, as seen in SDO AIA 193/171, EUVI A 195 and SUVI 285. Much later (after 05Z) some high post-eruptive arcades are seen in EUVI A 304 appearing from behind the limb, indicating the source that is far behind the limb, as seen from STEREO A. The much fainter shock can be best seen mostly as it pushes the streamer in the south south west towards the east. Likely deflection of about 10 to 20 degrees eastward relative to the source at W125 caused by a large coronal hole located to the northwest of Active Region 4012.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright, narrow CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-17T20:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 17/18:23Z to 18/03:09Z. The source of this event is a double peaked C9.8 and M1.0 flare from AR 4033 (N25E40) peaking at 2025-03-17T19:19Z and 2025-03-17T19:33Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption also seems to have a footpoint slightly further to the West at approx. N30E05, evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The field line loops appear to break off in stages, resulting in an earlier overlapping CME, CME: 2025-03-17T19:48Z. Both CMEs appear to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, outflow-like CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-18T06:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this event is continued dimming and field line movement following the C9.8 and M1.1 double peaked flare at 2025-03-17T19:04Z and 2025-03-17T19:25Z respectively.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-18T08:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen at approx. S30E65 in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193, along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 131 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faintly visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 data due to a data gap from 2025-03-18T15:39Z to 2025-03-19T03:09Z. The source appears to be a filament eruption beyond the E/NE limb starting around 2025-03-19T00:30Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131, 171, 193, and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint and wide loop CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Source is a filament eruption on or just beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, likely placing it at a longitude between W120 to W130, and spanning from approximately N10 to N40, with liftoff of filamentary material seen starting at 2025-03-19T03:45Z. Simultaneous opening field line movement can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, centered at N50, just to the north of the filament eruption, and possibly located further beyond the limb than the filament due to the faintness of this signature. A second, smaller loop of material centered at about N40 can be seen lifting off at 2025-03-19T06:15Z in STEREO A EUVI 304 which may be the source of the additional outflow seen in coronagraph imagery following this CME. Field line movement can also be seen on or beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 195. The quality and cadence of STEREO A COR2 imagery was affected during time of analysis due to a campaign scheduled to last from 2025-03-18 to 2025-03-24.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint but fast CME with an asymmetrical front, with a protruding nose to the south, seen directed to the west in SOHO with the start covered by the nighttime data gap in SOHO. Its source is the filament eruption seen on/behind the SW limb: as ejecta/prominence in AIA 304 (there are actually two ejectas - a more southern complex shaped loop-like prominence seen at 2025-03-19T22:50Z at latitude of -21, and a fan-shaped ejecta to the north of it seen at latitude of -7 at 2025-03-19T223:46Z. This eruption is also seen as fast opening of field lines behind the limb in AIA 193/171 starting at 2025-03-19T222:01Z and later (starting at 2025-03-19T223:21Z) as bright post-eruptive arcades on/behind the limb in AIA 131. There is an associated long duration occulted C6.0 flare peaking at 2025-03-20T00:07Z from behind the limb (bright arcades). It is possible that the flare is from former Active Region 4018 (S21W100).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint loop CME visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, with a faint flux rope feature more visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is the ejection of material from just beyond the southwest limb, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and ejecta starting around 2025-03-19T23:15Z in GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery. Post-eruptive brightening extends onto the disk spanning from about S10 to S15 and W80 to W90, as seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-03-19T23:40Z. Associated surrounding field line movement extends into the northern hemisphere on or beyond the western limb, and some northern deflection occurs as the material erupts.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Loop CME with brighter, narrower bulk and fainter shock visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 during a STEREO A COR2 data gap. The source of the CME appears to the ejection of material from near the vicinity of Active Region 4022 just near N08W75, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and brightening starting around 2025-03-20T17:24Z in SDO AIA 193 and 304 imagery. Faint flickering field lines far off the western limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 suggest that a component of this large scale eruption may be far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and to the S in two available frames of STEREO COR2A before a data gap begins at 2025-03-21T15:09Z. No source for this CME is observed in SDO and GOES imagery, suggesting a far-sided source alongside comparison between the CME direction in white light SOHO LASCO and STEREO COR2A imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint halo CME with a bulk visible mainly to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery (more easily seen in difference imagery). There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME appears to be a large dimming region centered near N02E07 starting around 2025-03-21T15:49Z with a southeast directionality based on the minor EUV wave visible in SDO/AIA 211 and 193 imagery. There's a large coronal hole situated E/SE of the dimming region and a separate coronal hole due west of the dimming region which may have contributed to the deflection visible on the solar disk in SDO/AIA imagery. This source location appears to be a sympathetic eruption to the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) seen to the SW in SDO/AIA 131 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the north-north-east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO A COR2 (along the northern streamer). Its source is the filament eruption seen beyond the north-north-east limb starting ~2025-03-22T07:18Z in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 304/284, with coronal signatures including a large prominence/ejecta (or even double ejecta) in AIA 171, SIVI 304/284 and as faint opening of field lines in AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption centered near N28E45 starting around 2025-03-22T13:45Z which exhibits northern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption centered near N18E52 starting around 2025-03-22T13:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. Dimming is visible north of the eruption site in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery starting around 2025-03-22T14:00Z and an opening of field lines can be observed over the northeast limb in GOES SUVI 284 imagery at this time. Additionally, post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 2025-03-22T14:30Z in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faint but visible as a partial halo directed towards the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is observed as a faint far-sided halo in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, and may be related to faint field line movement visible far beyond the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284 imagery starting around 2025-03-22T14:35Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Part of the constant outflow of multiple faint flows to the northeast. This front seems to be more eastward-directed compared to previous, more northern 2025-03-23T08:36Z CME/outflow. These two CMEs eventually seem to combine/overlap about halfway into C3's FOV around 13Z. No clear source has been found for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and SSE in STEREO COR2A. The source from this CME is uncertain and appears far-sided, via observed field line movement in SDO AIA 171 over the SE limb beginning around 2025-03-23T10:03Z and a triangulated STEREOCAT tool measurement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This narrow CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to an ongoing campaign. The source appears to be filament ejecta with associated field line movement to the SE in SDO/AIA 171, 193, and 304 starting around 2025-03-24T15:22Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME (less than ten degree half-width) first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 started at 2025-03-24T19:24Z. CME is also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning 2025-03-24T16:09Z. The source of this CME is possibly a small amount of ejecta from beyond the SE limb best seen in SDO AIA 304 starting at 2025-03-24T19:06Z. Some very faint field line movement from beyond the SE limb can also be seen in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 193 starting around 2025-03-24T19:04Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-35T04:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is filament ejecta seen along the NE limb beginning at approx. 2025-03-25T03:58Z in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3. Source is field line opening seen just beyond the SE limb at a latitude of about S16 and an approximated longitude of about E90 to E110 in SDO AIA 193 beginning at 2025-03-25T14:49Z. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery lasting from 2025-03-25T13:42Z to 2025-03-25T17:30Z, reduced image quality of SOHO LASCO C3 frames for timestamps following 2025-03-25T17:30Z, and by the regular overnight data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery which began at 2025-03-25T15:53Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-26T09:49Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is an occulted C6.5 flare from AR 14028 (S16W99) seen in SDO AIA 131 peaking at 2025-03-26T09:12Z. A small amount of filament ejecta is also visible in SDO AIA 304 along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2. This CME is not captured in available frames of SOHO LASCO C3 or STEREO A COR2, due to a data gap in SOHO LASCO which began at 2025-03-26T16:42Z and a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which began at 2025-03-26T13:23Z. The source is likely brightening seen at S20 and just beyond the East limb at approx. E100 to E110 in GOES SUVI 304 at 2025-03-26T15:01Z, as well as faint opening loops seen off the SE limb in GOES 284 at 2025-03-26T15:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption centered around S20E30. Filament liftoff starts around 2025-03-27T20:19Z in SDO AIA 304. Dimming is best seen in SDO AIA 193, and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193. The eruption is also visible from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195/304 imagery. The main bulk of the CME is preceded by a fainter, narrower loop in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-27T21:36Z that may be associated with an eruption from the same region, around S20E30.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible to the east/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME is still developing and only early imagery is available as a result. The source is related to an eruption and X1.1 flare from Active Region 14046 starting around 2025-03-28T15:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent wide opening of field lines can be observed in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery at this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-29T23:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 29/16:53Z to 30/03:38Z. The source of this event is an M1.9 flare from Active Region 4048 (S15E85) seen in SDO AIA 94 and 131. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A very faint loop-like CME to the southeast. There is a series of consecutive faint fronts, one of which is a bit brighter than the others and has been analyzed as the main front, but this brighter front is preceded by more faint fronts. The source of this CME is possibly the M1.5 flare from AR 14048 (S15E80) peaking at 2025-03-30T01:48Z. This CME is preceded by a narrow jet seen at 2025-03-29T23:12Z. It is possible that the jet is associated with the M1.9 flare, while this CME is associated with the M1.5 flare, both from AR 14048. The exact association with flares is not certain. Coronal signatures associated with the flares are relatively minor but very clear: an opening of field lines on/close to the SE limb seen in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-03-29T23:13Z, followed by post-eruptive arcades seen on the limb in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284. There is also minor ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-03-29T23:07Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-30T02:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 in later frames 29/16:53Z to 30/03:23Z. The source of this CME is field line opening seen along or just beyond the NW limb in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2; it is partially obscured by the pylon in C3, but its western edge is seen in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of it is likely an eruption with a very minor ejecta seen in SDO AIA 304/131/193 and GOES SUVI 284 at 2025-03-30T04:07Z just southwest of AR 4048 (S20E70) as post-eruptive arcades and small area dimming. The associated flare is a C3.5 flare observed in GOES-S, not in GOES-P, due to an eclipse.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME (somewhat brighter in STEREO COR2 coronagraph than in SOHO LASCO), seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Its source is a filament/ejecta on/close to the northwest limb, seen erupting starting at 2025-03-30T07:48Z in SDO AIA 171/403/131 and GOES SUVI 284/304, and seen as an opening of field lines and later as post-eruptive arcades/brightening in SDO AIA 193 extending to ~N22W70 but possibly centered around the northwest limb or even beyond the limb. The eruption is well seen in STEREO A EUV imagery happening to the east of AR 4035 (N16W94) and centered around ~N22W90.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap lasting from 2025-03-30T19:09Z to 2025-03-31T03:23Z. The source is likely related to an eruption and M1.5 flare from Active Region 14048 (S15E65) starting around 2025-03-30T23:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible near the southeast limb around this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This event is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-04-01T17:53Z. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint loop CME seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, SE in STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption seen starting at 2025-04-03T03:24Z from AR 4045 (S15W05) with Eastern deflection. Brightening and ejecta seen deflected to the east as seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-04-03T03:24Z. SDO AIA imagery was in a data gap which lasted from 2025-04-02T15:52Z to 2025-04-03T04:54Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the E/SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this event due to a data gap beginning at 2025-04-03T15:23Z. The source is a filament eruption visible along the SE limb in GOES SUVI 304 near S25E70 starting around 2025-03-04T17:32Z. Additionally moving/opening field lines are visible in GOES SUVI 171, 195, and 284, as well as brightening which is best seen in GOES SUVI 195. There is a data gap in SDO/AIA during the eruption for this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is a filament eruption from sightly over the east limb ~N15, observed as filament ejecta and field line movement starting around 2025-04-04T02:48Z in SDO AIA 131/171/193/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and directly S in STEREO COR2A. The source is likely dimming in the far southern area of the disk, centered around S60W20, observed in SDO AIA 193 around 2025-04-04T15:00Z. This may, unlikely, be related to a C4.4 flare from AR 14502 (S23W29) which peaked at 2025-04-04T14:46Z, it is difficult to discern if this flare erupted in this deflected direction, the dimming at S60W20 is an sympathetic eruption, or if the dimming at S60W20 is entirely separate. Thus it is not currently attributed as a source, and noted for completion of the analysis.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the N in STEREO A COR2. Source is a filament eruption from just beyond the NW limb. A prominence from just beyond the limb can be seen beginning to liftoff starting at 2025-04-04T16:08Z in GOES SUVI 304. Opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284 and ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 304 both show strong northern deflection of this eruption, with ejecta traveling nearly due north. STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 show that the prominence was centered at about N30 and spanned from W82-W92 (in SDO coordinates).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. No clear source of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A bright symmetrical partial halo seen to the east in both coronagraphs. Its source is a clear, wide opening of field lines behind the east limb seen ~2025-04-05T03:55Z in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284, later followed by post-eruptive arcades gradually appearing from behind the east limb, as seen in SDO AIA 193/304/131. It overlaps with a slightly later CME that is seen as a more full halo in STEREO A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A partial halo CME to the northeast, significantly overlapping with the 2025-04-05T04:00Z CME, and more clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery, in which its front is seen as a separate northeastern halo-like front, following the more eastern front of the earlier 2025-04-05T04:00Z CME. In SOHO its front is harder to trace because of the overlap of two CMEs. Its source is likely far behind the east limb and might be indicated by the large filament behind the northeast limb moving northward, as seen in AIA SDO 304 and GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery after 2025-04-05T05:00Z, although this filament is more likely to be the source of a later, more northern, 2025-04-05T09:48Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, as an opening of field lines is observed over the northeast limb in SDO AIA 171 imagery starting around 2025-04-06T03:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME with a faint loop-like leading edge visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is no clear source for this CME. The leading edge becomes diffuse partway through the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. There is no clear source for this eruption, however, due to its similarity to earlier eruptive activity, it is possible that the source is associated with the ongoing minor field line movement and minor eruptive activity from beyond the E/NE limb. The leading edge becomes diffuse early in the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view. There was no STEREO A COR2 imagery available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-06T20:53Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME to the northeast with the source and eruption observed slightly beyond the northeast limb starting around 2025-04-07T12:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is observed over the northeast limb around this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery, with post-eruptive arcades visible over the eastern limb starting around 2025-04-07T14:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the east in coronagraphs, following and overlapping with 2025-04-07T14:00Z CME. It is more clearly seen in running difference imagery than in the white light imagery. The source could be a very minor eruption/post eruptive arcade seen on/behind the east limb in SDO AIA 131/193 at 2025-04-07T14:12Z
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast loop CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the east-southeast in STEREO A COR2, quickly leaving the SOHO LASCO C2 field of view and comprised of a faint, asymmetric shock seen to the northeast. The likely source is an eruption seen near the vicinity of Active Region 4057 near N10E55 to E65 (after deflection), characterized by a brightening near the footpoints and a subsequent ejection of magnetic field flux seen occurring to the east starting around 2025-04-08T05:45Z, best in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 304. The eruption is also seen, though not as strongly in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284. Also associated with a type II radio burst with begin time 05:53Z and velocity 456 km/s.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the east-southeast in STEREO A COR2, quickly leaving the SOHO LASCO C2 field of view. The likely source is a secondary eruption seen near the vicinity of Active Region 4057 near N10E55 to E65 (after deflection) following CME: 2025-04-08T06:00Z characterized by a brightening near the footpoints and a subsequent ejection of plasma seen occurring to the east starting around 2025-04-08T08:00Z, best in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A very faint narrow but fast jet to the northeast in both coronagraphs. Its source could be a narrow filament eruption off the northeast limb seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 at ~2025-04-09T06:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow jet CME visible to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-09T18:53Z. There was no clear source for this CME; there are several small instances of field line movement in the Western hemisphere of the disk and on the West limb, but none distinct enough to consider as a candidate source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is some filament ejecta from AR 14048 (S16W71) observed in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-04-10T08:12Z, along with field line movement in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Extremely faint and narrow CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2. The leading edge becomes diffuse before leaving the C2 field of view. Source is unclear, but there is continual flickering and field line movement from AR 4055 (N08W43), including a small instance of southward directed field line movement seen starting at 2025-04-11T12:45Z in SDO AIA 171. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-11T11:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Wide loop CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2. Source is an eruption near the NE limb, seen as a rising loop of opening field lines starting at 2025-04-11T20:40Z in SDO AIA 171. There are two connected rising loops seen on the E limb, which lift off together in the same eruption. One spans from approx. N22 to N30 along E70, while the other spans from approx. N35 to N50 along E90. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-11T11:23Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-12T03:24Z. Also visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely far-sided as there are not any good source candidates on the Earth-facing disk. A far-sided source is supported by triangulation from SWPC_CAT measurement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-12T06:36Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely far-sided as there are not any good source candidates on the Earth-facing disk. A far-sided source is supported by triangulation from SWPC_CAT measurement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-12T10:48Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely far-sided as there are not any good source candidates on the Earth-facing disk. There is some faint field line movement from beyond the WSW limb starting around 2025-04-12T10:24Z best seen in GOES SUVI 284 that could be related to the source of this CME. A far-sided source is supported by triangulation from SWPC_CAT measurement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-12T12:00Z. Also seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is likely a filament eruption beginning around 2025-04-12T11:21Z that is best seen in SDO AIA 304. The filament is centered around N25-35W0-10. Measurement of the CME indicates some deflection toward the NE.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A southeastern halo with a very complex system of several fronts that seem to be moving/expanding in unison. It is difficult to differentiate the bulk vs. shock components of the CME. There seems to be the more dense more southern part to the SW and also a fainter more 'halo' front. The source is a filament erupting starting 2025-04-13T05:00ZZ, stretching from S30E01 to S15W25 as seen in SDO AIA 304 (with more minor dimming reaching S01W30 as seen in SDO AIA 193), and centered ~S18W15.

Source is a bit uncertain, but a candidate source is dimming seen near AR 4060 (N09E30) spanning from N00 to N15 and E20 to E30, starting around 2025-04-13T07:00Z in SDO AIA 193.

note: This CME is visible to the east/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to faint field line movement visible over the eastern limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery starting around 2025-04-14T13:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A bright, relatively narrow high southern latitude CME along a streamer to SSW in both coronagraphs.  The CME source is the wide opening/movement of field lines on/behind southwest limb starting ~2025-04-14T14:24Z, as seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption on the southeast limb starting around 2025-04-14T14:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193 and 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines can be observed over the southeast limb around this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Additionally, post-eruptive arcades begin to form around 2025-04-15T17:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-16T00:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. note: Very narrow (with <10 deg half-width), faint, fast jet to the northeast in both coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2) mostly seen in running difference imagery (almost not noticeable in white light images). note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-19T00:00Z. Also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is partially obscured by the pylon. The start of the CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting from 2025-04-18T22:38Z to 2025-04-19T02:38Z, and following the data gap the leading edge is out of the field of view. This CME is associated with an M4.4 flare peaking at 2025-04-18T23:50Z and ejecta from on/beyond the SE limb (~S29E90). A Type II radio burst was also observed. The flare and associated ejecta are seen across SDO AIA and GOES SUVI wavelengths but are most clearly seen in SDO AIA 304 and SDO AIA 131. A wider, possible shock front is visible in a few early frames of SOHO LASCO C2, but quickly fades away and was determined to not be measurable. The CME experiences continued southward deflection through propagation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Semi-faint CME to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 (also visible in GOES-19/CCOR-1). The source is field line movement seen to the south beyond the limb in SDO/AIA 171 and 193 as well as in GOES SUVI 335 starting around 2025-04-19T16:48Z. This is likely a far-sided event. There is no STEREO A imagery for this event due to a data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Two heavily overlapping flux rope CMEs from the same source seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is two instances of significant dimming and opening field lines seen from the same location, AR 4065 (S31E10), starting at 2025-04-22T06:37Z then at 2025-04-22T07:24Z. There appears to be southern deflection in the UV imagery. Post eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 193 starting at 2025-04-22T08:13Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. It has a bright core that fills more to the right side of the CME with a more faint leading edge. The source is an eruption from AR 14060 (N08W90) on/just beyond the western limb associated with an M1.3 flare, filament ejecta, and post-eruptive arcades as best seen in GOES SUVI 131, 304, and 171. This source is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and SDO/AIA imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-24T00:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames, however a majority of this CME is blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, but fits between SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2 suggest a far sided source. This CME does not have a very clearly defined front.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The source of this event is a filament eruption seen along the NW limb (centered at approx. N30W90, footpoints located at approx. N40W50 and N25W100) in SDO AIA, STEREO A EUVI and GOES SUVI 304 with early liftoff beginning at approx. 24/05:24Z. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, GOES SUVI 284, and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the southwest by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-24T08:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The source of this event is a Southern deflected eruption from AR 4065 (S31W22) beginning at approx. 24/13:34Z. This eruption and subsequent Southern dimming can be seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211. This deflection is likely due to the Active Region's proximity to a large positive polarity coronal hole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

Brightening and a small amount of ejecta can be seen in SDO AIA 304. Brightening and field line movement can be seen in SDO AIA 193, 171. Ejecta can be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 at timestamp 2025-04-26T10:15Z.

The source of this CME is a filament eruption from the area of Active Region 14065 (S31W51) which is located in the middle of a large southern coronal hole. The filament eruption starts around 2025-04-26T19:00Z as seen in SDO/AIA 304, 193, 211, and 171 spanning the area of ~S30W45 to ~S40W55.

The start time is somewhat ambiguous as the CME is very faint and less defined in SOHO LASCO C2. There is no good source candidate on the Earth-facing disk. However, a couple of possibilities are some minor movement along a filament centered about 15 degrees N of AR 14073 beginning around 2025-04-27T14:36Z and a minor puff of ejecta from approximately N40E30 beginning around 2025-04-27T15:16Z.

The source at first glimpse and with higher confidence appears to be an eruption just beyond the western limb as seen mostly by quickly darkening field lines off the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171 around 2025-04-29T14:00Z, but with low confidence may be associated with Active Region 4070 (S12W51) as some minor darkening in the active region seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-04-29T14:00Z. Measurement will be created assuming the limb-related source.

The source of this event is slow rising and opening field lines seen along the NE limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.

This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-29T19:23Z. The source of this event is a C7.3 flare from AR 4065 (S31W91) and subsequent filament eruption as seen exhibiting Southern deflection in SDO AIA 131, 304 and GOES SUVI 304. Wide opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.

note: Narrow, fast CME to the SW in STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. There is currently a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The source is seen as moving/opening field lines starting around 2025-05-01T08:39Z to the SW in SDO/AIA 193 and 171. An associated small filament eruption is also visible in SDO/AIA 304 and STEREO A EUVI 304 to the SW. This eruption is likely associated with old AR 14065 which rotated off the Earth-facing disk late on 2025-04-29. The estimated longitudes of the source are (~S31W110 to ~S31W125) based on calculation of average rotation and visible inspection of STEREO A EUV imagery. This active region is situated within a coronal hole which may attribute to deflection.
