Associated moving/opening field lines are visible in SDO/AIA 171 along the southern limb.

This CME overlaps with earlier CME: 2025-05-30T06:38Z which is associated with the M3.4 flare, where as this event is more associated with the subsequent dimming following the flare.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Full-halo CME first seen in GOES-19 CCOR-1. Also seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 after the beginning of a downlink period with data streaming in starting at about 2025-05-31T01:00Z. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-05-30T19:09Z. The source is an M8.1 flare from AR 14100 (N12E12). A significant area of opening field lines and dimming can be seen from near AR 14100 (N12E12) in SDO AIA 193/171/131/304 and GOES SUVI 284/304 beginning at 2025-05-30T23:47Z, immediately after the flare. Dimming and field line movement extends along a nearby filament which spans across most of the Earth-facing disk, stretching from approximately N30E05 to S15W35, snaking through the entire NW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk in a shape resembling the number '3'. It appears that most of the filamentary material ejected is from the upper lobe of the '3', and departs from approximately N10W15.

The filament appears to be potentially wrapping around the limb in both SOHO and STEREO A instruments, so it is hard to estimate the center of this erupting filament. Source is a filament eruption beyond the NW limb as seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304, and seen close to the limb in STEREO A EUVI 304. There are two lobes of this CME, each corresponding to a piece of filament that erupted. Both pieces of filamentary material can be seen erupting simultaneously in GOES SUVI 304 imagery, so both lobes are therefore considered as one CME. The filament is located at latitude N40 and spanned from approximately W90 to W130. Gradual liftoff is seen starting as early as 2025-07-05T06:23Z in GOES SUVI 304. There is a data gap in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery such that the start of the filament liftoff is not captured.

Liftoff can also be seen from the NW quadrant in GOES SUVI 304, but it appears that most of the filamentary material may have fallen back to the solar surface.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Very faint jet-like CME with a front to the west seen only in difference imagery in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and not seen in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs; not clearly seen in white light imagery. No source was found for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow faint CME seen W in SOHO difference imagery, also seen faintly in GOES CCOR-1 coronagraph but not seen in STEREO A COR2. No source was found for this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-07-05T22:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption from AR 14127 (S19W45) as seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211. This event is likely deflected toward the North by Southern coronal hole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning t 2025-07-06T02:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption from AR 14127 (S19W49) beginning at approx. 2025-07-06T01:40Z as seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211. This CME is likely deflected Northward by a Southern oriented coronal hole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-07-06T09:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption from approx. S20E60 beginning at approx. 2025-07-06T08:40Z as seen in SDO AIA 304. Field line movement is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and to the NE in STEREO A COR2. Source is a filament eruption, with liftoff seen starting as early as 2025-07-07T01:13Z in SDO AIA 304 and spanning from N40E45 to N30W10, and possibly extending further to N30W30. Post-eruptive brightening and ejecta is seen in SDO AIA 304, GOES SUVI 304, and STEREO A EUVI 304. Dimming and post-eruptive arcades can be seen in SDO AIA 193 and STEREO A EUVI 193. Ejecta and field line movement is seen in SDO AIA 171. This CME is heavily obstructed by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is uncertain. One candidate source is a small instance of brightening seen at S05W50, between AR 4129 (N02W46) and AR 4128 (S06W56) in GOES SUVI 284 at 2025-07-07T05:47Z. Another candidate source is a possible eruption from AR 4127 (S19W62) indicated by gradually opening field lines in SDO AIA 171 starting at 2025-07-07T06:00Z and by brightening at AR 4127 seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 in the frame timestamped 2025-07-07T05:45Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint, diffuse CME observed to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source may be weak field line movement near/just inside the SE limb starting as early as 2025-07-07T13:59Z in GOES SUVI 284, and slow dimming in SDO AIA 193. This front is preceeded by a faint, too diffuse to track outflow beginning at 2025-07-07T13:36Z in LASCO C2.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow CME first seen in the SE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-07-07T22:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is an area of slow field line opening seen originating from along the SE limb seen in SDO AIA 193 beginning at 2025-07-07T21:31Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow CME first seen to the SW in GOES CCOR-1 beginning at 2025-07-07T23:00Z, as well as in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen originating from near AR 14127 S20W75 seen beginning at approx. 2025-07-07T22:24Z in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and more NNE in STEREO A COR2. The source is an eruption on or just beyond the NE limb around N22, with an M2.4 flare visible in SDO AIA 171 which began at 2025-07-08T03:42Z. Also observed well in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 171/195/284 as wide field line opening, an EUV wave, and a brief post eruptive arcade. This source eruption may have triggered simultaneous fronts in other directions, observed as CME 2025-07-08T04:36Z (NE more in ecliptic) and CME 2025-07-08T04:48Z (far north).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: This CME is very faint but visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is unknown and likely far-sided, but may be related to an eruption visible on or slightly beyond the southwest limb near latitude S50 as seen in STEREO A EUVI imagery starting around 2025-07-09T11:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the northwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is blocked by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk that align with the direction of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME observed to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and SW in STEREO A COR2. No source is observed in SDO, GOES, or STEREO A imagery, which combined with the triangulation of coronagraph imagery concludes that this source is far-sided.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and to the SW in STEREO A COR2. Source is a filament eruption from beyond the SE limb from the perspective of SDO AIA and GOES SUVI and beyond the SW limb from the perspective of STEREO A EUVI. Diffuse ejecta from beyond the SE limb can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting as early as 2025-07-11T09:52Z. In STEREO A EUVI 304, there may possibly be a rising loop from beyond the SW limb seen between the frames with timestamps 2025-07-11T07:45Z-08:15Z, followed by wider opening field lines between the frames with timestamps 2025-07-11T08:15Z-08:45Z. The first available frame of SOHO LASCO C2 in which the leading edge is well defined is the frame at timestamp 2025-07-11T10:24Z after a brief gap caused by a scheduled calibration of SOHO LASCO.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A relatively narrow CME with a messy front visible to SSW in white light (as well as in running difference) imagery in all three coronagraphs. Seen more to the south and more faintly in STEREO A COR2. Its likely source is a filament seen erupting starting at 2025-07-12T08:45Z near the SW limb, as seen in SDO AIA imagery, centered very approximately at (S35W60). The source is seen in more detail in STEREO A EUV 304/195 imagery than in other EUV imagers: in STEREO EUVI 195 two simultaneous eruptions cam be seen - one in the AR 4134 (~S23W90), and the other in the filament located SE of this AR (~S35W45).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Fast CME seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR1 but so far covered by the gap in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. Its source could be an eruption in the NE quadrant, with medium size dimming seen in AIA 193 starting after 2025-07-12T12:00Z and centered around (N20E52). There is also activity in AR 4136 (N19E32) at the time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Very narrow jet-like CME (less than 10 degree half-width) first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T16:12Z. CME is only visible in SOHO LASCO C2 and is much easier to see in running difference imagery. CME fades before leaving FOV of SOHO LASCO C2. The source is likely a small eruption from on/beyond the NE limb around 2025-07-13T14:42Z best seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Source is uncertain; there is no clear source in available UV imagery of the disk. Leading edge is not visible in STEREO A COR2. Source is uncertain, but may be subtle field line movement seen on or beyond the SE limb GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1
